00:00:37.399 --> 00:00:38.930
AKSHAY THAKKER: Now, yeah.

00:00:38.930 --> 00:00:40.610
Well, welcome.

00:00:40.610 --> 00:00:46.570
I am delighted to be here, like
I said, partly because you're

00:00:46.570 --> 00:00:47.606
from Pune.

00:00:47.606 --> 00:00:49.275
Could you tell us a
little bit about--

00:00:49.275 --> 00:00:50.900
LILLETE DUBEY: Of
course, I have to say

00:00:50.900 --> 00:00:54.940
that it is a very epic moment
for me to be here at Google.

00:00:54.940 --> 00:00:55.760
Really.

00:00:55.760 --> 00:01:00.560
And I'm not just saying that
because, today like, Durga,

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:04.129
you know, Durga is this
goddess with eight hands,

00:01:04.129 --> 00:01:05.570
Google is our Durga.

00:01:05.570 --> 00:01:08.310
You know, whatever we
need comes from Google.

00:01:08.310 --> 00:01:10.130
So it's not just for that.

00:01:10.130 --> 00:01:11.870
It's because today,
I was thinking

00:01:11.870 --> 00:01:14.670
a lot about how I would
start chatting with you all.

00:01:14.670 --> 00:01:16.200
And I thought of my father.

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:18.750
My father was what is
called a Renaissance man.

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:22.100
A da Vinci of our times
in his own way, because he

00:01:22.100 --> 00:01:23.770
was an engineer by profession.

00:01:23.770 --> 00:01:26.360
He was a physicist by passion.

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:30.080
His passion was the special
theory of relativity.

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:31.490
When he got married
to my mother,

00:01:31.490 --> 00:01:34.400
he told her I have one
mistress, and that's physics.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:37.310
So don't bother me, because I'm
going to spend a lot of time

00:01:37.310 --> 00:01:39.130
with her.

00:01:39.130 --> 00:01:43.160
And he used to get every
few years, the Britannica,

00:01:43.160 --> 00:01:44.570
as it got updated.

00:01:44.570 --> 00:01:46.310
And my earliest memories--

00:01:46.310 --> 00:01:47.610
he had a fabulous library.

00:01:47.610 --> 00:01:49.135
He was very fond of books.

00:01:49.135 --> 00:01:52.410
So there was one sort of
room half-dedicated to books.

00:01:52.410 --> 00:01:53.660
We used to get the Britannica.

00:01:53.660 --> 00:01:56.920
And I thought of him today, and
I said, what an epic moment.

00:01:56.920 --> 00:01:59.240
Dad, you will be
smiling today up

00:01:59.240 --> 00:02:01.610
there, because I'm a Googler.

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:04.130
And he worked till he was 88.

00:02:04.130 --> 00:02:05.630
He got cancer when he was 88.

00:02:05.630 --> 00:02:08.330
And he had a computer
in his office.

00:02:08.330 --> 00:02:11.496
But suddenly, he told
me, I want a laptop.

00:02:11.496 --> 00:02:13.370
I said, do you even know
how to use a laptop?

00:02:13.370 --> 00:02:14.328
He said, I'll learn it.

00:02:14.328 --> 00:02:15.560
It's not a big deal.

00:02:15.560 --> 00:02:18.120
And we got on to it.

00:02:18.120 --> 00:02:21.440
And I remember Google,
because I said, Dad--

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:22.430
he was very low.

00:02:22.430 --> 00:02:23.900
It was a few months
before he died.

00:02:23.900 --> 00:02:26.120
I said, do you want to see
what you've done in your life?

00:02:26.120 --> 00:02:27.995
Do you want to see some
of your achievements?

00:02:27.995 --> 00:02:29.490
He said, how would I do that?

00:02:29.490 --> 00:02:32.570
So I said, we hit Google,
and we find your name,

00:02:32.570 --> 00:02:34.110
and we see what you've done.

00:02:34.110 --> 00:02:36.960
And my dad gave talks
at Imperial College,

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:39.350
wrote for "Nature."

00:02:39.350 --> 00:02:44.660
He gave talks at King's College,
lots of places, on physics.

00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:49.010
So that was the last time I saw
him smile, and I saw his eyes

00:02:49.010 --> 00:02:55.100
light up, because he saw so many
sites on which he was there.

00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:58.310
And I remembered him
with great, great love

00:02:58.310 --> 00:03:00.190
today, when I was
coming to Google.

00:03:00.190 --> 00:03:01.419
I have to share that.

00:03:01.419 --> 00:03:02.960
And the other thing
I wanted to share

00:03:02.960 --> 00:03:05.941
was that my mother, she
was obviously not there,

00:03:05.941 --> 00:03:07.940
because she's never printed
anything-- you know,

00:03:07.940 --> 00:03:08.870
published anything.

00:03:08.870 --> 00:03:12.920
And you get to Google if
you've been somewhere,

00:03:12.920 --> 00:03:14.480
you know, on print.

00:03:14.480 --> 00:03:17.570
I mean, that's how I
assume it's all collated.

00:03:17.570 --> 00:03:19.574
And my mother's
feeling very left out.

00:03:19.574 --> 00:03:20.990
And I said, how
do I cheer her up?

00:03:20.990 --> 00:03:23.870
So I said, you
know, Mom, your dad

00:03:23.870 --> 00:03:26.960
was the first FRCP, the
Fellow of the Royal College

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:28.850
of Physicians from Edinburgh.

00:03:28.850 --> 00:03:30.290
And he also--

00:03:30.290 --> 00:03:33.590
Sikh by religion, and
we have the holy book.

00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:35.900
And my grandfather
also translated

00:03:35.900 --> 00:03:39.020
the first two gospels,
let's say, of that holy book

00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:40.670
into English.

00:03:40.670 --> 00:03:42.930
So I said, I'm sure he's there.

00:03:42.930 --> 00:03:44.330
So we Googled him.

00:03:44.330 --> 00:03:48.160
And in one of the
sites that were there,

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:50.810
he mentioned all his
children, including my mother.

00:03:50.810 --> 00:03:53.930
So I said, hey, you're
dead too on the internet.

00:03:53.930 --> 00:03:55.944
And she was so thrilled.

00:03:55.944 --> 00:03:57.860
She was so thrilled that
her father was there.

00:03:57.860 --> 00:04:00.770
So I said before we talk
about anything else,

00:04:00.770 --> 00:04:02.330
I have to tell you that.

00:04:02.330 --> 00:04:06.980
Because sort of my journey in
my life, which is peculiar,

00:04:06.980 --> 00:04:09.459
because I will tell you
about where I come from

00:04:09.459 --> 00:04:11.000
and how sometimes
the things that you

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
get from your parents, which
are very strong characteristics,

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:17.490
also help you to break things
and do things on your own.

00:04:17.490 --> 00:04:20.240
So I was remembering my
parents because of Google.

00:04:20.240 --> 00:04:22.520
And I said before I talk
about anything else,

00:04:22.520 --> 00:04:24.560
I have to thank
Google, because two

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:28.070
of the best moments of my
dad's life before he went

00:04:28.070 --> 00:04:29.629
were because of Google.

00:04:29.629 --> 00:04:30.920
AKSHAY THAKKER: That's amazing.

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:34.490
Thank so much for--

00:04:34.490 --> 00:04:36.744
you know, it's stories
like these that keep

00:04:36.744 --> 00:04:37.910
us coming to work every day.

00:04:37.910 --> 00:04:38.150
LILLETE DUBEY: Of course.

00:04:38.150 --> 00:04:38.650
Of course.

00:04:38.650 --> 00:04:39.770
Of course.

00:04:39.770 --> 00:04:44.660
I mean, obviously, we
become like little babies,

00:04:44.660 --> 00:04:49.640
dependent on that Google
Map, that Google application

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:51.290
for almost anything.

00:04:51.290 --> 00:04:52.790
So that goes without
saying, but I'm

00:04:52.790 --> 00:04:56.750
talking about a very personal
thing that touched me,

00:04:56.750 --> 00:05:00.302
where Google really became far
more than just an application.

00:05:00.302 --> 00:05:02.510
AKSHAY THAKKER: Yeah, that
was a very touching story.

00:05:02.510 --> 00:05:04.460
Thank you again
for sharing that.

00:05:04.460 --> 00:05:09.280
So you studied
English literature.

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:13.080
You know, a few
decades ago, how did

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:14.610
you convince your
parents to study

00:05:14.610 --> 00:05:17.040
anything that didn't
sound like medicine,

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:17.999
or engineering, or law?

00:05:17.999 --> 00:05:19.456
LILLETE DUBEY: Very
good questions,

00:05:19.456 --> 00:05:20.740
because I was coming to that.

00:05:20.740 --> 00:05:23.520
That these great parents,
wonderful, wonderful parents

00:05:23.520 --> 00:05:27.450
that I had, were
quite unique also.

00:05:27.450 --> 00:05:33.101
I come from a very long lineage
of academics and professionals.

00:05:33.101 --> 00:05:33.600
OK.

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:36.690
So my father was an engineer,
a Lahore engineer, in college

00:05:36.690 --> 00:05:38.340
before partition.

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:41.840
And my mother was a
doctor, a gynecologist,

00:05:41.840 --> 00:05:43.890
at Lady Hardinge in Delhi.

00:05:43.890 --> 00:05:45.910
And they were both
very independent,

00:05:45.910 --> 00:05:52.049
strong-minded, principled,
super intelligent people.

00:05:52.049 --> 00:05:53.840
And they didn't get
married in those days--

00:05:53.840 --> 00:05:55.840
I'm talking about
65, 70 years ago,

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:59.220
till they were in their
30's, which was unheard of.

00:05:59.220 --> 00:06:06.720
So they gave me some very strong
sort of values and good DNA

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:09.390
on many, many, many aspects.

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:12.780
But they were also very
clear that they didn't

00:06:12.780 --> 00:06:15.090
want me to get into the arts.

00:06:15.090 --> 00:06:19.500
So my father wanted me to be at
the least a nuclear physicist.

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:22.350
At the very least,
if not go into space.

00:06:22.350 --> 00:06:24.670
And my mother wanted
me to be a path

00:06:24.670 --> 00:06:28.740
breaking, you know, sort of a
Nobel Prize winning biologist,

00:06:28.740 --> 00:06:29.730
or whatever.

00:06:29.730 --> 00:06:31.250
Medicine was her field.

00:06:31.250 --> 00:06:32.520
And it was not just her.

00:06:32.520 --> 00:06:34.320
You see, her sister
was a doctor.

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:35.730
Her father was a doctor.

00:06:35.730 --> 00:06:37.560
His father was a doctor.

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:41.010
And my father-- in fact, when
my father's brother studied

00:06:41.010 --> 00:06:42.780
at Mayo in the
'50s, Mayo Clinic,

00:06:42.780 --> 00:06:45.570
and set up the All India
Institute of Medical Sciences,

00:06:45.570 --> 00:06:49.350
and the cousins were doctors.

00:06:49.350 --> 00:06:52.110
So it was this deluge
of professionals.

00:06:52.110 --> 00:06:54.600
And when I said
after school that I

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:57.349
don't want to do anything
any more to do with science,

00:06:57.349 --> 00:06:58.890
I studied science
up to school, and I

00:06:58.890 --> 00:07:00.730
said I don't have that brain.

00:07:00.730 --> 00:07:02.170
I have a left brain.

00:07:02.170 --> 00:07:03.600
I don't want to use that.

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:05.520
And my father was horrified.

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:08.250
You know, because, you see,
he was so well-informed.

00:07:08.250 --> 00:07:11.630
He could talk to you
about your subject.

00:07:11.630 --> 00:07:13.380
He could talk to my
mother about medicine,

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:15.960
my husband about economics,
my brother-in-law,

00:07:15.960 --> 00:07:18.850
who's a game theorist
about game theory.

00:07:18.850 --> 00:07:21.810
So he made everyone feel like--

00:07:21.810 --> 00:07:26.790
that generation was a
generation of people

00:07:26.790 --> 00:07:30.210
with a great deal of
intellectual curiosity

00:07:30.210 --> 00:07:33.390
about-- we become a
generation of specialists.

00:07:33.390 --> 00:07:35.760
Not me, more your
generation, which

00:07:35.760 --> 00:07:38.340
is very important, because
depth is important,

00:07:38.340 --> 00:07:39.550
and focus is important.

00:07:39.550 --> 00:07:40.860
It's so competitive.

00:07:40.860 --> 00:07:44.310
But they had a breadth
of vision, my father,

00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:48.270
that I haven't seen very
much in recent times.

00:07:48.270 --> 00:07:50.130
And it's quite wonderful.

00:07:50.130 --> 00:07:51.970
In the sense of, I
remember I was reading,

00:07:51.970 --> 00:07:55.419
Arundhati's Roy's book,
"The God of Small Things."

00:07:55.419 --> 00:07:56.710
She just won the Booker for it.

00:07:56.710 --> 00:07:58.380
She was sort of
a friend of mine.

00:07:58.380 --> 00:07:59.670
And I, said you have
to read this book.

00:07:59.670 --> 00:08:02.160
He said, well, what do you think
is so great about this book?

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:03.951
Why do you think she
got the Booker for it?

00:08:03.951 --> 00:08:06.660
Or if I said, you know,
Jhumpa Lahiri got a Pulitzer.

00:08:06.660 --> 00:08:08.227
He said, well,
what do you think?

00:08:08.227 --> 00:08:09.060
What is the reasons?

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:11.540
I had given him a reason for
him to even look at the book,

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:13.290
because it was a waste
of time, otherwise.

00:08:13.290 --> 00:08:14.670
He never read fiction.

00:08:14.670 --> 00:08:19.290
And he loved technology.

00:08:19.290 --> 00:08:20.580
He loved new things.

00:08:20.580 --> 00:08:23.529
He loved he loved the
cosmos, reading about that.

00:08:23.529 --> 00:08:26.070
So he felt there were so many
important things to read about,

00:08:26.070 --> 00:08:28.140
why would you bother
reading about literature

00:08:28.140 --> 00:08:30.700
all the time for God's
sake and study it?

00:08:30.700 --> 00:08:33.121
So he was very, very
upset because he

00:08:33.121 --> 00:08:34.620
could quote Shakespeare
to me better

00:08:34.620 --> 00:08:36.179
than I could quote it to him.

00:08:36.179 --> 00:08:37.679
And he wondered,
why the hell did

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:42.210
I want to waste five years of
my master's studying literature?

00:08:42.210 --> 00:08:44.091
And he could never
understand it.

00:08:44.091 --> 00:08:45.840
And then, you know how
Indian fathers are.

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:46.770
He said, OK.

00:08:46.770 --> 00:08:48.854
Then I get a second masters
in mass communication,

00:08:48.854 --> 00:08:51.228
just because I was scared that
theatre may not pay me any

00:08:51.228 --> 00:08:51.780
money.

00:08:51.780 --> 00:08:54.870
So [INAUDIBLE] luckily,
so I had a lot of offers

00:08:54.870 --> 00:08:56.374
in advertising,
none of which I did.

00:08:56.374 --> 00:08:58.040
He said, OK, you're
getting married now.

00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:00.840
You're your husband's
responsibility.

00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:03.380
I don't care what you do.

00:09:03.380 --> 00:09:05.670
And my mother was more--

00:09:05.670 --> 00:09:08.640
she just gave me
this very strong,

00:09:08.640 --> 00:09:13.020
you know, at the sort of strong
matriarchal, very feisty,

00:09:13.020 --> 00:09:16.430
independent woman
who endures this.

00:09:16.430 --> 00:09:18.764
There were two things I
learned, one from my father,

00:09:18.764 --> 00:09:20.680
from my mother, which
was very important to me

00:09:20.680 --> 00:09:22.290
as a philosophy.

00:09:22.290 --> 00:09:25.020
Because after I decided that
I was going to do theater,

00:09:25.020 --> 00:09:27.540
I was very silly, because
when I was doing the masters,

00:09:27.540 --> 00:09:29.790
my father said, OK, if
you must do something,

00:09:29.790 --> 00:09:31.890
you have to excel at it.

00:09:31.890 --> 00:09:35.250
Don't do something if you
go half-hearted, half-baked.

00:09:35.250 --> 00:09:38.010
Go to Radha, study theater.

00:09:38.010 --> 00:09:39.600
Or go to the NSC
and study theater.

00:09:39.600 --> 00:09:44.130
Don't do just this sort of
dilettante-ish way of doing it.

00:09:44.130 --> 00:09:49.780
So his philosophy was, you
will excel if you do something.

00:09:49.780 --> 00:09:53.100
You'll have a chance to
excel only if you really

00:09:53.100 --> 00:09:58.140
work hard and hone your skills
and put everything into it.

00:09:58.140 --> 00:10:02.640
And my mother, one thing that
was very important to me,

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:04.002
was that two things.

00:10:04.002 --> 00:10:06.210
One was that she was such
an independent-minded woman

00:10:06.210 --> 00:10:08.126
that when I said, no, I
don't want to do this.

00:10:08.126 --> 00:10:09.760
She said, OK, do what you want.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:11.012
Do exactly what you want.

00:10:11.012 --> 00:10:12.970
In fact, she used to
always tell me two things.

00:10:12.970 --> 00:10:15.770
She used to tell me,
you know, in those days,

00:10:15.770 --> 00:10:19.490
we didn't have eggs
that we could freeze.

00:10:19.490 --> 00:10:22.310
So men, you have to get married,
because you need children.

00:10:22.310 --> 00:10:25.550
But otherwise, it's not
that important to have

00:10:25.550 --> 00:10:28.840
men in your life.

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:30.800
I'm sure she's smiling
today, because today,

00:10:30.800 --> 00:10:32.260
women are freezing their eggs.

00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:33.400
Just go to a sperm bank.

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:35.358
I want that, that, that,
and they just tick off

00:10:35.358 --> 00:10:37.110
all their specifications.

00:10:37.110 --> 00:10:38.510
And we're done.

00:10:38.510 --> 00:10:41.210
That is true
empowerment, really,

00:10:41.210 --> 00:10:43.640
aside from financial
sort of empowerment,

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:46.570
which to me, is the
beginning of any empowerment.

00:10:46.570 --> 00:10:49.550
You know, in India, we talk
so much about empowerment

00:10:49.550 --> 00:10:53.240
and women's sort of--

00:10:53.240 --> 00:10:55.550
that they don't have
enough independence.

00:10:55.550 --> 00:10:57.530
But it's a very
simple thing to me

00:10:57.530 --> 00:11:00.050
that, in India,
half our population

00:11:00.050 --> 00:11:03.570
is financially not independent.

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:06.290
So a woman takes
so much from a man

00:11:06.290 --> 00:11:08.550
because she simply can't
walk out of that door.

00:11:08.550 --> 00:11:10.340
She can't go back
to her parents,

00:11:10.340 --> 00:11:13.850
and she has no resources,
no education, no literacy

00:11:13.850 --> 00:11:16.230
to look after herself.

00:11:16.230 --> 00:11:19.131
So I think before any
other kind of empowerment

00:11:19.131 --> 00:11:21.380
that we talk about, we just
really, in India at least,

00:11:21.380 --> 00:11:24.440
we have to talk about that,
grassroots, getting them up

00:11:24.440 --> 00:11:27.560
there to be able to say, I
will not take this nonsense.

00:11:27.560 --> 00:11:30.080
I will walk out of this door.

00:11:30.080 --> 00:11:33.800
But my mother, actually, was
I think a very forward looking

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:35.137
woman, that she said all that.

00:11:35.137 --> 00:11:37.470
And another thing she told
me, which was very important,

00:11:37.470 --> 00:11:41.930
which is all connected to
my being in the theater,

00:11:41.930 --> 00:11:45.620
was that, look, never look for
other people and other sources

00:11:45.620 --> 00:11:46.250
of happiness.

00:11:46.250 --> 00:11:48.590
Be the architect of
your own happiness.

00:11:48.590 --> 00:11:50.690
Everything else is a bonus.

00:11:50.690 --> 00:11:52.160
So if your kids love you, great.

00:11:52.160 --> 00:11:53.390
Your husband loves, great.

00:11:53.390 --> 00:11:54.800
If he doesn't, well, you're OK.

00:11:54.800 --> 00:11:56.540
You're OK because you
are the wellspring

00:11:56.540 --> 00:11:58.260
of your own happiness.

00:11:58.260 --> 00:12:02.700
So all this sort of combined to
shape me to become what I am.

00:12:02.700 --> 00:12:05.846
So anyway, because they were
so strong and independent,

00:12:05.846 --> 00:12:07.470
I also could be strong
and independent.

00:12:07.470 --> 00:12:09.870
And I said, hey, I
don't want to do this.

00:12:09.870 --> 00:12:11.750
I don't want to be
a nuclear physicist.

00:12:11.750 --> 00:12:14.510
But what happened was a strange
thing, which I must share,

00:12:14.510 --> 00:12:17.480
because it will happen
to a lot of young people.

00:12:17.480 --> 00:12:23.040
That because I did something
that I was sort of impelled

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:27.240
from inside me to do, I felt
that this was a calling,

00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:30.750
the performing arts
was my calling,

00:12:30.750 --> 00:12:33.150
but I was not able
to articulate why it

00:12:33.150 --> 00:12:35.430
was that important right then.

00:12:35.430 --> 00:12:39.150
And I used to feel, right
up to till I was 40, that I

00:12:39.150 --> 00:12:40.380
was a bit of a dilettante.

00:12:40.380 --> 00:12:42.421
My dad had this thing,
he'd come and see my plays

00:12:42.421 --> 00:12:44.610
and say, oh, Lillete,
well done, well done,

00:12:44.610 --> 00:12:45.780
you know, kind of thing.

00:12:45.780 --> 00:12:48.450
But it was like, well, if
you must play at all this,

00:12:48.450 --> 00:12:50.110
then so be it.

00:12:50.110 --> 00:12:51.720
I started doing films.

00:12:51.720 --> 00:12:55.112
I well recognized, and all that.

00:12:55.112 --> 00:12:56.820
But it didn't make
any difference to him.

00:12:56.820 --> 00:12:59.160
You know, he preferred
my theatre work anyway.

00:12:59.160 --> 00:13:01.440
And my mother was
a great beauty,

00:13:01.440 --> 00:13:03.510
and all her sisters
were great beauties.

00:13:03.510 --> 00:13:06.510
But in our family, it was
like, God gave you all that.

00:13:06.510 --> 00:13:07.950
So let's not worry
about all that.

00:13:07.950 --> 00:13:09.300
Work on yourself.

00:13:09.300 --> 00:13:13.230
So it was a very unusual
kind of a background.

00:13:13.230 --> 00:13:16.050
And so I decided
to do what it did,

00:13:16.050 --> 00:13:21.000
but it took me a long time to
be comfortable with the fact

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.900
that what I did had
a lot of meaning,

00:13:23.900 --> 00:13:27.960
had a lot of relevance,
that it was very important.

00:13:27.960 --> 00:13:29.670
And very often,
young people, when

00:13:29.670 --> 00:13:33.470
they choose alternative careers,
which are not your engineer,

00:13:33.470 --> 00:13:37.990
doctor, lawyer, computer
scientist, whatever,

00:13:37.990 --> 00:13:43.440
the sort of general
well-acknowledged sort of life,

00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:46.940
a serious life, earnest
kind of professions.

00:13:46.940 --> 00:13:51.870
They feel a little like they've
disappointed their parents.

00:13:51.870 --> 00:13:54.390
You know, I mean, today,
sport is recognized

00:13:54.390 --> 00:13:56.670
because it's very paying.

00:13:56.670 --> 00:13:58.170
And other professions
are recognized

00:13:58.170 --> 00:13:59.520
because they're very paying.

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:03.300
But let's say 30 years ago,
these people played cricket,

00:14:03.300 --> 00:14:08.370
but they were not
earning a lot of money.

00:14:08.370 --> 00:14:10.680
So things have changed a lot.

00:14:10.680 --> 00:14:12.240
But still, I see
young people who

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:14.550
are struggling
because this is not

00:14:14.550 --> 00:14:16.890
the profession that their
parents would like them to do.

00:14:16.890 --> 00:14:18.310
Not at all.

00:14:18.310 --> 00:14:20.910
So then you have to
show your success.

00:14:20.910 --> 00:14:22.200
And it's not easy.

00:14:22.200 --> 00:14:25.290
A creative career is
the most difficult one

00:14:25.290 --> 00:14:28.980
to even assess success.

00:14:28.980 --> 00:14:32.250
You have very easy
yardsticks in other fields.

00:14:32.250 --> 00:14:34.440
You know, a doctor has
a roaring practice,

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:37.170
or he earns a huge
sort of amount of money

00:14:37.170 --> 00:14:41.120
at NYU Medical Center, or
you know Sloan, or whatever.

00:14:41.120 --> 00:14:43.854
But how do you judge
the success of someone

00:14:43.854 --> 00:14:44.770
in the creative world?

00:14:44.770 --> 00:14:48.030
It's extremely difficult.
And it changes all the time.

00:14:48.030 --> 00:14:50.780
Today, you're God, you have
three films that are bomb,

00:14:50.780 --> 00:14:51.780
and you're out of there.

00:14:51.780 --> 00:14:52.980
You're nobody.

00:14:52.980 --> 00:14:57.990
So it's such an elusive,
ephemeral kind of success

00:14:57.990 --> 00:14:59.770
that we're talking about.

00:14:59.770 --> 00:15:01.810
AKSHAY THAKKER: Well,
and these days, it

00:15:01.810 --> 00:15:03.660
sounds like the number
of YouTube followers

00:15:03.660 --> 00:15:06.118
and Twitter followers you have
is a good measure of success

00:15:06.118 --> 00:15:07.060
as well.

00:15:07.060 --> 00:15:08.680
LILLETE DUBEY: I
didn't even know I o.

00:15:08.680 --> 00:15:10.190
AKSHAY THAKKER:
But to your point,

00:15:10.190 --> 00:15:12.290
it does change over time.

00:15:12.290 --> 00:15:13.800
LILLETE DUBEY: Yes, yes, yes.

00:15:13.800 --> 00:15:16.050
AKSHAY THAKKER: You
did a lot of work,

00:15:16.050 --> 00:15:21.420
obviously, in Bollywood in
the arena, but also in the UK

00:15:21.420 --> 00:15:22.990
and in Hollywood.

00:15:22.990 --> 00:15:27.030
How do you compare
the two experiences?

00:15:27.030 --> 00:15:28.450
LILLETE DUBEY: It's very simple.

00:15:28.450 --> 00:15:33.150
My heart, my soul, my body,
belongs to the theater.

00:15:33.150 --> 00:15:34.830
I'm a dyed in the
wool theatre person.

00:15:34.830 --> 00:15:38.360
And it's weird, because if you
meet a theater person, when

00:15:38.360 --> 00:15:40.560
I was doing "Marigold, I
met Judi Dench and Maggie

00:15:40.560 --> 00:15:43.980
Smith, who are died in the
wool, 60 years with the National

00:15:43.980 --> 00:15:45.360
Theater in London.

00:15:45.360 --> 00:15:47.520
So there is an
immediate connect.

00:15:47.520 --> 00:15:50.950
It's a different kind of
binding, bonding, that happens.

00:15:50.950 --> 00:15:53.070
So my heart, everything
belongs to theatre.

00:15:53.070 --> 00:15:55.260
Because for me,
theater's where it's at.

00:15:55.260 --> 00:15:58.440
It's the last pure bastion left.

00:15:58.440 --> 00:16:05.400
It is still relatively
untainted by commerce.

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:07.790
Now, I tell you a little
bit about my theater work,

00:16:07.790 --> 00:16:09.540
because it's important
in the light of all

00:16:09.540 --> 00:16:11.010
the questions you'll ask.

00:16:11.010 --> 00:16:14.140
I worked as an actress
for 15 years, like a diva,

00:16:14.140 --> 00:16:16.920
doing all the lead roles with
a person called Barry John,

00:16:16.920 --> 00:16:18.250
and had a whale of a time.

00:16:18.250 --> 00:16:19.833
And then I started
to decide to set up

00:16:19.833 --> 00:16:21.750
my own company 27 years ago.

00:16:21.750 --> 00:16:25.680
So now you know exactly,
like a fossil, how old I am.

00:16:25.680 --> 00:16:30.660
And I decided I want to
do that for two reasons.

00:16:30.660 --> 00:16:34.470
Also, like I told you, there
was this slow understanding,

00:16:34.470 --> 00:16:38.350
why are the performing arts and,
therefore, theater important?

00:16:38.350 --> 00:16:39.810
Why are they important?

00:16:39.810 --> 00:16:42.510
What does art bring to us?

00:16:42.510 --> 00:16:45.030
What is so important about art?

00:16:45.030 --> 00:16:47.130
And it was like
an epiphany at 40

00:16:47.130 --> 00:16:52.636
for me, that you know, really,
art is what illuminates life.

00:16:52.636 --> 00:16:53.760
It's what Shakespeare says.

00:16:53.760 --> 00:16:56.040
It's a mirror up to nature.

00:16:56.040 --> 00:16:56.820
We all live.

00:16:56.820 --> 00:16:58.347
We live a wonderful life.

00:16:58.347 --> 00:16:59.930
There are, of course,
Eureka moments--

00:16:59.930 --> 00:17:03.690
a mathematician proves a theorem
which hasn't been proved,

00:17:03.690 --> 00:17:06.150
or a problem that hasn't been
proved for 50 years, or 30

00:17:06.150 --> 00:17:07.650
years, and wow.

00:17:07.650 --> 00:17:09.180
It's a Eureka moment.

00:17:09.180 --> 00:17:12.150
A runner breaks that
marathon record.

00:17:12.150 --> 00:17:15.569
You know, there are Eureka
moments in every field.

00:17:15.569 --> 00:17:19.170
But for me, I feel that,
as a whole, the whole body

00:17:19.170 --> 00:17:22.230
of the performing arts, and arts
as a whole, including painting,

00:17:22.230 --> 00:17:28.339
music, all that, these are the
things that really originalize,

00:17:28.339 --> 00:17:33.590
illuminate our lives, you know,
expand our horizons in ways,

00:17:33.590 --> 00:17:37.180
which to me, if you ask me what
is divinity, it is the arts.

00:17:37.180 --> 00:17:40.490
When we hear a wonderful piece
of music, when we see and read

00:17:40.490 --> 00:17:42.290
an astounding poem.

00:17:42.290 --> 00:17:46.220
You know, we come closer to
something which is beyond us.

00:17:46.220 --> 00:17:49.490
So to me, it's really
spiritual almost.

00:17:49.490 --> 00:17:53.660
And it's something that
absolutely opens up

00:17:53.660 --> 00:17:57.860
dimensions in our mind, which
we don't even know exist.

00:17:57.860 --> 00:18:00.460
So I realize the value of it.

00:18:00.460 --> 00:18:03.780
And more than that,
the value of--

00:18:03.780 --> 00:18:07.310
you know, we live in
a technological age.

00:18:07.310 --> 00:18:10.220
OK, we're going more and
more into that little screen

00:18:10.220 --> 00:18:11.570
for everything.

00:18:11.570 --> 00:18:13.670
Jug Saraiya, this wonderful
columnist in India,

00:18:13.670 --> 00:18:15.650
once wrote that,
"Many, many years ago,

00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:18.290
that soon, there will
be one small little room

00:18:18.290 --> 00:18:21.650
with a small little man with a
small little smartphone sitting

00:18:21.650 --> 00:18:27.390
in a corner getting sex, food,
clothes, whatever he wants,

00:18:27.390 --> 00:18:28.996
you know, in that
small little room."

00:18:28.996 --> 00:18:29.870
In a way, it's funny.

00:18:29.870 --> 00:18:31.340
In a way, it's scary.

00:18:31.340 --> 00:18:36.280
Because the human experience
is getting so contracted.

00:18:36.280 --> 00:18:37.790
So contracted.

00:18:37.790 --> 00:18:39.200
And a weird thing's happening.

00:18:39.200 --> 00:18:43.340
As much as we are looking for
that sort of the virtual world

00:18:43.340 --> 00:18:46.410
in which we live, and the
digital world in which we live,

00:18:46.410 --> 00:18:47.420
we also crave--

00:18:47.420 --> 00:18:51.650
because are ultimately
fireside storytellers.

00:18:51.650 --> 00:18:55.070
This is our DNA as well.

00:18:55.070 --> 00:18:57.830
So how do we connect
to each other?

00:18:57.830 --> 00:19:01.534
Our common humanity is
through shared experience.

00:19:01.534 --> 00:19:02.450
Why do I love theater?

00:19:02.450 --> 00:19:03.533
Because it's not complete.

00:19:03.533 --> 00:19:06.510
If he's not there and I'm
not there, I could be here.

00:19:06.510 --> 00:19:07.260
It's not complete.

00:19:07.260 --> 00:19:07.790
He's there.

00:19:07.790 --> 00:19:08.910
It's not complete.

00:19:08.910 --> 00:19:11.900
We need those two
people to connect.

00:19:11.900 --> 00:19:13.460
So it's not just theater.

00:19:13.460 --> 00:19:14.150
It's music.

00:19:14.150 --> 00:19:14.660
It's dance.

00:19:14.660 --> 00:19:17.330
But specially theater,
especially theatre.

00:19:17.330 --> 00:19:19.690
I can still dance.

00:19:19.690 --> 00:19:21.950
You see, for
myself, I can dance.

00:19:21.950 --> 00:19:23.240
I can sing for myself.

00:19:23.240 --> 00:19:24.920
I can paint for myself.

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:26.970
But can I perform for myself?

00:19:26.970 --> 00:19:28.790
No, I cannot.

00:19:28.790 --> 00:19:32.370
It has to be you with me
in that shared experience.

00:19:32.370 --> 00:19:35.022
And that's the beginning
of our common humanity.

00:19:35.022 --> 00:19:36.980
That's how we start
connecting with each other.

00:19:36.980 --> 00:19:37.850
You know?

00:19:37.850 --> 00:19:41.207
And we tell stories, which are
universal, let me tell you.

00:19:41.207 --> 00:19:43.040
When I did a play called
"Dance Like a Man,"

00:19:43.040 --> 00:19:45.290
in New York, the same one
that ran Off-Broadway,

00:19:45.290 --> 00:19:49.400
"The New York Times" had
never covered an Indian play.

00:19:49.400 --> 00:19:53.000
And my raison d'etre with
starting a company was I

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:58.280
wanted to talk about the Indian
voice, Indian English voice,

00:19:58.280 --> 00:20:00.950
original voice,
in Indian theater.

00:20:00.950 --> 00:20:01.910
Why in English?

00:20:01.910 --> 00:20:03.650
Because then, he can
understand my plays.

00:20:03.650 --> 00:20:06.020
He can understand.

00:20:06.020 --> 00:20:08.570
He can listen to the
stories, the plays,

00:20:08.570 --> 00:20:10.430
that have been written
by our playwrights.

00:20:10.430 --> 00:20:13.290
Very often people have asked me
to come, including in America,

00:20:13.290 --> 00:20:14.831
why don't you come
in direct to play?

00:20:14.831 --> 00:20:16.840
I said, but then, who
will tell our stories?

00:20:16.840 --> 00:20:18.800
You have plenty of people
to tell your stories.

00:20:18.800 --> 00:20:20.090
We don't have anyone.

00:20:20.090 --> 00:20:22.580
We have a handful of
people to tell our stories.

00:20:22.580 --> 00:20:24.770
They need us to
tell our stories,

00:20:24.770 --> 00:20:28.240
to tell a [NON-ENGLISH]
play, put it out there,

00:20:28.240 --> 00:20:32.000
or [NON-ENGLISH],, or
zillions of very talented--

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:35.490
I remember I did a play once,
and this very, very, very

00:20:35.490 --> 00:20:39.170
well-known group from America
came and, this woman said, wow,

00:20:39.170 --> 00:20:40.850
that was fabulous.

00:20:40.850 --> 00:20:41.960
Who's written the play?

00:20:41.960 --> 00:20:45.140
So I said this guy
called Mahesh Elkunchwar.

00:20:45.140 --> 00:20:46.580
He's Indian?

00:20:46.580 --> 00:20:48.800
I said, but it's so--

00:20:48.800 --> 00:20:49.610
fantastic.

00:20:49.610 --> 00:20:51.276
I said, you know, I
don't know if that's

00:20:51.276 --> 00:20:52.660
a compliment or an insult?

00:20:52.660 --> 00:20:55.761
Because the way you're
asking me, it's like, oh,

00:20:55.761 --> 00:20:57.510
an Indian couldn't
have written that play.

00:20:57.510 --> 00:20:59.690
She's like, no, I really
mean it's so sophisticated.

00:20:59.690 --> 00:21:01.930
I don't think anybody--
so I said, thank you.

00:21:01.930 --> 00:21:04.040
You're just putting your foot
in your mouth again, and again,

00:21:04.040 --> 00:21:04.250
and again.

00:21:04.250 --> 00:21:04.850
You know?

00:21:04.850 --> 00:21:06.230
Just stop.

00:21:06.230 --> 00:21:06.950
You know?

00:21:06.950 --> 00:21:09.680
So I realized that's it.

00:21:09.680 --> 00:21:13.010
We have to-- so we are,
without being too immodest,

00:21:13.010 --> 00:21:14.600
the most traveled
company in India.

00:21:14.600 --> 00:21:17.690
We've done 3,000 shows in
India and abroad, right

00:21:17.690 --> 00:21:22.420
from Wellington, New Zealand
to Portland, Seattle.

00:21:22.420 --> 00:21:24.274
And all through most
of the countries.

00:21:24.274 --> 00:21:25.440
I haven't been to China yet.

00:21:25.440 --> 00:21:27.060
I haven't been to Russia yet.

00:21:27.060 --> 00:21:28.760
I haven't been to
South America yet.

00:21:28.760 --> 00:21:30.390
A few continents left.

00:21:30.390 --> 00:21:33.150
But plenty have been taken to.

00:21:33.150 --> 00:21:35.180
And let me tell you the
most interesting thing.

00:21:35.180 --> 00:21:38.010
So I did it because not just
that I wanted to platform

00:21:38.010 --> 00:21:40.150
Indian work, but I
wanted to see-- you know,

00:21:40.150 --> 00:21:41.500
the Indians have a habit.

00:21:41.500 --> 00:21:44.190
And I don't mean this badly, of
patting ourselves on the back

00:21:44.190 --> 00:21:46.270
and saying, fabulous,
that was wonderful.

00:21:46.270 --> 00:21:48.160
Especially you go to
see a movie premiere,

00:21:48.160 --> 00:21:49.270
they're so hypocritical.

00:21:49.270 --> 00:21:51.270
Everything's mind-blowing, and
then they walk out of the room

00:21:51.270 --> 00:21:52.950
and say, oh, god,
it was terrible.

00:21:52.950 --> 00:21:55.170
So you know?

00:21:55.170 --> 00:21:56.470
But Indians do that.

00:21:56.470 --> 00:21:57.960
They sort of buck each other up.

00:21:57.960 --> 00:21:59.950
And they don't really
tell you the truth.

00:21:59.950 --> 00:22:02.490
So when you take an Indian play
outside and do it out there

00:22:02.490 --> 00:22:05.550
in Kuala Lumpur, or in Bangkok,
no one's going to be generous.

00:22:05.550 --> 00:22:06.550
If it's good, it's good.

00:22:06.550 --> 00:22:08.790
If it's bad, it's awful.

00:22:08.790 --> 00:22:11.520
So to take a play
about [INAUDIBLE]----

00:22:11.520 --> 00:22:13.990
now, [INAUDIBLE] you know, we
have a caste system in India,

00:22:13.990 --> 00:22:15.364
which is horrible,
which is still

00:22:15.364 --> 00:22:19.800
sort of still in the
fabric of our lives,

00:22:19.800 --> 00:22:21.530
which is awful absolutely.

00:22:21.530 --> 00:22:23.960
So there were you know
the very, very educated,

00:22:23.960 --> 00:22:26.240
the less educated, the
warriors, and then the people

00:22:26.240 --> 00:22:28.915
who clean your houses, and there
were always the untouchables.

00:22:28.915 --> 00:22:31.260
And Gandhi fought against.

00:22:31.260 --> 00:22:34.450
And so, it's a story about them.

00:22:34.450 --> 00:22:39.470
It's like, a black guy from
Harlem, very, very dirt poor,

00:22:39.470 --> 00:22:45.020
marrying an Upper West
Side rich, rich white girl.

00:22:45.020 --> 00:22:45.800
You know?

00:22:45.800 --> 00:22:48.450
So for me, that
story was about that.

00:22:48.450 --> 00:22:49.910
It was about culture clash.

00:22:49.910 --> 00:22:50.570
You know?

00:22:50.570 --> 00:22:52.370
And however liberal
we are, you just

00:22:52.370 --> 00:22:53.690
have to scratch the surface.

00:22:53.690 --> 00:22:56.064
And then if your daughter is
marrying someone like that--

00:22:56.064 --> 00:22:58.940
[INAUDIBLE] intellectuals,
armchair intellectuals saying,

00:22:58.940 --> 00:23:00.530
of course, we must integrate.

00:23:00.530 --> 00:23:02.030
We must do this, and all that.

00:23:02.030 --> 00:23:04.110
And then when it comes
into your own living room,

00:23:04.110 --> 00:23:05.450
you can't handle it

00:23:05.450 --> 00:23:09.200
So I was shocked that the play
like this could touch people

00:23:09.200 --> 00:23:11.600
in Kuala Lumpur, could touch--

00:23:11.600 --> 00:23:12.890
the subcontinent's OK.

00:23:12.890 --> 00:23:15.410
They understand all
these references.

00:23:15.410 --> 00:23:20.600
But for it to work in a Kuala
Lumpur, or a place like London,

00:23:20.600 --> 00:23:23.660
where non-Indians were
seeing it, but they got it.

00:23:23.660 --> 00:23:25.220
They got all that.

00:23:25.220 --> 00:23:28.516
It didn't have to be--
and I don't peddle it

00:23:28.516 --> 00:23:29.640
in a sort of sweetened way.

00:23:29.640 --> 00:23:31.160
We talk as we talk.

00:23:31.160 --> 00:23:33.770
If I'm Gujarati, I talk
like a [NON-ENGLISH]

00:23:33.770 --> 00:23:35.390
or a [NON-ENGLISH].

00:23:35.390 --> 00:23:37.400
And if I'm a South
Indian, I talk like that.

00:23:37.400 --> 00:23:39.367
I mean, clear, but
with an accent.

00:23:39.367 --> 00:23:41.450
And people said, oh, you
can't do plays like this.

00:23:41.450 --> 00:23:42.408
Nobody will understand.

00:23:42.408 --> 00:23:44.300
I said, hell, I come to America.

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:47.824
I go hear James Earl Jones doing
"Fences" with a Harlem accent,

00:23:47.824 --> 00:23:49.490
and I have to say,
hello, what was that,

00:23:49.490 --> 00:23:50.850
what was that, what was that?

00:23:50.850 --> 00:23:52.400
I didn't understand
half the play.

00:23:52.400 --> 00:23:54.500
But I still loved
the experience.

00:23:54.500 --> 00:23:56.022
So we have to
enter those worlds.

00:23:56.022 --> 00:23:57.980
We're not going to give
it to you on a platter.

00:23:57.980 --> 00:24:00.301
Come, I will explain what
this means and that means.

00:24:00.301 --> 00:24:00.800
No, no, no.

00:24:00.800 --> 00:24:02.091
We're going to explain nothing.

00:24:02.091 --> 00:24:05.060
You come here, you
enter our world.

00:24:05.060 --> 00:24:09.020
And then you see the
universality of the stories.

00:24:09.020 --> 00:24:10.880
Because like the
"Natyashastra," which

00:24:10.880 --> 00:24:14.780
is a great book,
5,000 year old book

00:24:14.780 --> 00:24:16.760
that talks about the
performing arts--

00:24:16.760 --> 00:24:19.130
I don't think there's an
older book than that--

00:24:19.130 --> 00:24:21.740
talks about the
seven emotions only

00:24:21.740 --> 00:24:25.480
that human beings go through,
the nine [INAUDIBLE],,

00:24:25.480 --> 00:24:29.340
so the dance, then
music, then theater.

00:24:29.340 --> 00:24:30.410
And I was shocked.

00:24:30.410 --> 00:24:32.750
I knew why "The New York
Times" is so respected,

00:24:32.750 --> 00:24:34.640
because when we
performed there, they

00:24:34.640 --> 00:24:36.920
gave us a half page
review on their Arts Page

00:24:36.920 --> 00:24:38.690
on a Friday arts review.

00:24:38.690 --> 00:24:41.060
It's like a Bible.

00:24:41.060 --> 00:24:43.390
So I didn't know that they
came quietly, they saw it,

00:24:43.390 --> 00:24:45.800
they quietly wrote this
review, and it came out.

00:24:45.800 --> 00:24:47.977
And my friends in the
theater and in New York

00:24:47.977 --> 00:24:50.060
said, my god, you've been
performing for 20 years,

00:24:50.060 --> 00:24:52.070
and "The New York
Times" never covered us.

00:24:52.070 --> 00:24:54.200
So they covered us, and
what was very interesting

00:24:54.200 --> 00:24:57.775
was, I believe it was a very
tough critique, and all that.

00:24:57.775 --> 00:24:59.150
And he gave us a
glowing reviews.

00:24:59.150 --> 00:25:00.191
But that's not the point.

00:25:00.191 --> 00:25:04.130
At the end of it, he
quoted the "Natyashastra."

00:25:04.130 --> 00:25:07.500
And I said, my god,
this old white guy,

00:25:07.500 --> 00:25:11.210
who was like 70 years old, he
really has done his homework.

00:25:11.210 --> 00:25:13.449
And he's gone to
the "Natyashastra,"

00:25:13.449 --> 00:25:14.990
and he gave us the
biggest compliment

00:25:14.990 --> 00:25:18.620
I've ever got, because he
said, "The lofty ideals

00:25:18.620 --> 00:25:22.460
of the "Natyashastra" may
be very difficult for humans

00:25:22.460 --> 00:25:25.370
to achieve, but this play
comes pretty damn close."

00:25:25.370 --> 00:25:28.960
And I thought that was such
a marvelous compliment.

00:25:28.960 --> 00:25:31.546
And another one important
wrote about how,

00:25:31.546 --> 00:25:33.420
you know, you enter this
play, and you think,

00:25:33.420 --> 00:25:37.460
oh silk saris, and Indian
music, and flowers in the hair,

00:25:37.460 --> 00:25:40.420
and about classical
[INAUDIBLE] dances.

00:25:40.420 --> 00:25:42.319
And are we going
to get any of this?

00:25:42.319 --> 00:25:44.360
And at the end of the
play, you say, my god, this

00:25:44.360 --> 00:25:47.570
is as familiar to me, this
story with its relationships,

00:25:47.570 --> 00:25:53.340
and its conflicts, and its
everything, as my kitchen sink.

00:25:53.340 --> 00:25:57.620
So that is the idea, that we
open doors of understanding,

00:25:57.620 --> 00:25:59.730
we celebrate our
differences, but we

00:25:59.730 --> 00:26:01.380
open doors of understanding.

00:26:01.380 --> 00:26:05.370
And in that, art has
such a huge role to play.

00:26:05.370 --> 00:26:06.100
Such a huge.

00:26:06.100 --> 00:26:09.600
Role sports does, but sports
is more in that arena of,

00:26:09.600 --> 00:26:14.620
you know, at some point, we
get a little nationalistic.

00:26:14.620 --> 00:26:15.120
OK?

00:26:15.120 --> 00:26:16.037
Let's admit it.

00:26:16.037 --> 00:26:17.370
In art, you don't get like that.

00:26:17.370 --> 00:26:19.920
If there's some
wonderful singer--

00:26:19.920 --> 00:26:24.490
I heard a fabulous band called
[INAUDIBLE] from Algeria.

00:26:24.490 --> 00:26:26.600
The desert music, the
Grammy award winner.

00:26:26.600 --> 00:26:28.430
They just held them
recently in Mumbai.

00:26:28.430 --> 00:26:30.620
It didn't matter I didn't
understand their language.

00:26:30.620 --> 00:26:31.960
I didn't understand their--

00:26:31.960 --> 00:26:34.990
I understood nothing of the
reference or the context.

00:26:34.990 --> 00:26:38.280
But I said, wow, what music.

00:26:38.280 --> 00:26:40.410
So it elevates us.

00:26:40.410 --> 00:26:42.490
It takes us somewhere else.

00:26:42.490 --> 00:26:45.060
It celebrates all
the differences.

00:26:45.060 --> 00:26:47.880
But it just brings
us all together

00:26:47.880 --> 00:26:51.360
in such an amazing
way, that I realize,

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:52.800
that's why I love the arts.

00:26:52.800 --> 00:26:54.690
That's why I want
to be where I am.

00:26:54.690 --> 00:26:58.440
And my theater especially,
not just Indian,

00:26:58.440 --> 00:27:02.070
it's also about
exploring subjects.

00:27:02.070 --> 00:27:04.740
Again, film is so
determined by commerce

00:27:04.740 --> 00:27:07.890
that, unless it's a very small,
very independent film that

00:27:07.890 --> 00:27:12.390
is exploring something
very explosive, in theater,

00:27:12.390 --> 00:27:13.380
you can do that.

00:27:13.380 --> 00:27:14.220
You can do that.

00:27:14.220 --> 00:27:16.800
I mean, my plays go
from sexual abuse

00:27:16.800 --> 00:27:23.400
to the first main screenplay on
homosexuality, which is still

00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:26.490
a punishable offense in India.

00:27:26.490 --> 00:27:27.330
Can you believe it?

00:27:27.330 --> 00:27:29.730
How archaic is that?

00:27:29.730 --> 00:27:31.890
To Gandhi's
philosophy, and how did

00:27:31.890 --> 00:27:33.630
Gandhi had these
out of the box--

00:27:33.630 --> 00:27:35.820
we talk about out
of the box ideas.

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:39.370
Each and every idea of
Gandhi's was out of the box,

00:27:39.370 --> 00:27:41.790
[NON-ENGLISH],,
nonviolence, [NON-ENGLISH]..

00:27:41.790 --> 00:27:43.950
Everything, if you examine,
it's a brilliant play,

00:27:43.950 --> 00:27:45.540
it's got many awards.

00:27:45.540 --> 00:27:48.180
And when you see an Arab
sitting after the play

00:27:48.180 --> 00:27:51.600
and talking to me about Gandhi,
and it is so fascinating,

00:27:51.600 --> 00:27:53.760
and you think this
is a country--

00:27:53.760 --> 00:27:55.740
what would this Arab
know about Gandhi?

00:27:55.740 --> 00:27:56.910
But he's fascinated.

00:27:56.910 --> 00:27:59.250
It's fascinating,
because the play

00:27:59.250 --> 00:28:04.227
was a play that explored Gandhi,
was sort of the common jewel.

00:28:04.227 --> 00:28:05.310
And there was the Mahatma.

00:28:05.310 --> 00:28:07.060
And there were these
debates between them.

00:28:07.060 --> 00:28:07.710
You know?

00:28:07.710 --> 00:28:10.179
And through that, he said,
you know, you could do this.

00:28:10.179 --> 00:28:11.220
He said, I can't do that.

00:28:11.220 --> 00:28:12.860
I'm just an ordinary fellow.

00:28:12.860 --> 00:28:13.890
How can I do all this.

00:28:13.890 --> 00:28:15.280
He said, why?

00:28:15.280 --> 00:28:16.786
One person can
make a difference.

00:28:16.786 --> 00:28:18.160
He said, oh, don't
talk nonsense.

00:28:18.160 --> 00:28:20.060
One person can do anything.

00:28:20.060 --> 00:28:23.350
And that's how he said, be
the change you want to be.

00:28:23.350 --> 00:28:25.320
Because one person can do it.

00:28:25.320 --> 00:28:27.940
Two people, what are their
names, who started Google?

00:28:27.940 --> 00:28:28.940
Two guys sat together.

00:28:28.940 --> 00:28:29.960
AKSHAY THAKKER: Yeah,
Larry Page and Sergey Brin.

00:28:29.960 --> 00:28:31.751
LILLETE DUBEY: Yeah,
they just sat together

00:28:31.751 --> 00:28:34.955
one day, two PhD students
and said, hey, let's do this.

00:28:34.955 --> 00:28:35.830
And that's all it is.

00:28:35.830 --> 00:28:37.538
And you guys know it
better than anybody.

00:28:37.538 --> 00:28:41.150
It's just an idea,
the germ of an idea.

00:28:41.150 --> 00:28:44.217
So to have an Arab
talking about Gandhi

00:28:44.217 --> 00:28:46.550
was very strange, with all
their robes and all this out,

00:28:46.550 --> 00:28:48.850
and they discussed it
after the play in Dubai

00:28:48.850 --> 00:28:51.040
and in Moscow, they used
to talk about Gandhi.

00:28:51.040 --> 00:28:52.560
So it could be
Gandhi's philosophy.

00:28:52.560 --> 00:28:53.652
It could be Zen Buddhism.

00:28:53.652 --> 00:28:55.360
I've done a play on
Buddhism, because you

00:28:55.360 --> 00:29:00.940
know zen comes from Dhyana,
and Dhyana is meditation.

00:29:00.940 --> 00:29:04.870
And it's founded by [INAUDIBLE]
King, who was so weak,

00:29:04.870 --> 00:29:06.570
he couldn't breathe.

00:29:06.570 --> 00:29:09.180
The King was going
to throw him away.

00:29:09.180 --> 00:29:11.580
The King was this wrestler
and, you know, very macho,

00:29:11.580 --> 00:29:12.160
and all that.

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:15.060
And he has this little
weakling of a prince who's

00:29:15.060 --> 00:29:16.680
puffing away because
he's a blue baby,

00:29:16.680 --> 00:29:17.970
and he says, just chuck him.

00:29:17.970 --> 00:29:19.140
We don't need him.

00:29:19.140 --> 00:29:23.580
And the Brahmin, who did
the [INAUDIBLE] for him,

00:29:23.580 --> 00:29:25.080
says, no, I'll keep it.

00:29:25.080 --> 00:29:26.560
And he teaches him yoga.

00:29:26.560 --> 00:29:30.030
And he teaches him how to read,
and he teaches him exercises,

00:29:30.030 --> 00:29:34.300
so that he learns and he
creates the martial arts

00:29:34.300 --> 00:29:41.460
and becomes a 28 sort of sort
of high priest of Buddhism,

00:29:41.460 --> 00:29:45.210
goes there to China,
and they couldn't

00:29:45.210 --> 00:29:48.880
pronounce Dhyana, so it became,
tian, chan, john, zane, zan.

00:29:48.880 --> 00:29:50.930
Bu tthe time it hit
Japan, it was zen.

00:29:50.930 --> 00:29:51.900
You know?

00:29:51.900 --> 00:29:55.110
And I was so fascinated,
because I said.

00:29:55.110 --> 00:29:56.520
This is from India.

00:29:56.520 --> 00:29:58.380
Nobody even knows this.

00:29:58.380 --> 00:30:00.700
And then we did it in Hong
Kong, Singapore, Bangkok,

00:30:00.700 --> 00:30:02.430
that whole belt over there.

00:30:02.430 --> 00:30:03.660
And people were fascinated.

00:30:03.660 --> 00:30:05.810
And I said, hello, it
all comes from here.

00:30:05.810 --> 00:30:09.390
I, mean I'm sorry, but what
can I do if everything just

00:30:09.390 --> 00:30:11.230
started in India?

00:30:11.230 --> 00:30:12.450
The zero came from here.

00:30:12.450 --> 00:30:13.830
This came from there.

00:30:13.830 --> 00:30:18.146
So the subjects I choose
are very eclectic.

00:30:18.146 --> 00:30:20.646
You know, now, "Gauhar," when
I was doing "Gauhar," everyone

00:30:20.646 --> 00:30:27.590
said, a woman in 1902 singing
some old classical Indian

00:30:27.590 --> 00:30:29.600
music, I mean, OK.

00:30:29.600 --> 00:30:32.630
So she was the one that sang
first on a vinyl record.

00:30:32.630 --> 00:30:33.582
So she made history.

00:30:33.582 --> 00:30:35.540
And she was like an Amy
Winehouse of her times,

00:30:35.540 --> 00:30:37.377
without the drugs, I think.

00:30:37.377 --> 00:30:38.960
Maybe she was doing
opium on the side.

00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:39.980
Who knows?

00:30:39.980 --> 00:30:42.140
But she sang.

00:30:42.140 --> 00:30:43.120
She composed.

00:30:43.120 --> 00:30:46.130
She wrote her own lyrics at 15.

00:30:46.130 --> 00:30:48.260
She sang in 20 languages.

00:30:48.260 --> 00:30:51.260
She was on, you know,
like little matchboxes.

00:30:51.260 --> 00:30:55.670
And whatever kind of publicity
they had all over Europe,

00:30:55.670 --> 00:30:56.510
she was huge.

00:30:56.510 --> 00:30:58.190
She was a rock star of her time.

00:30:58.190 --> 00:30:59.565
And people had
been uninterested.

00:30:59.565 --> 00:31:02.900
They said, well, who was
interested in this thing?

00:31:02.900 --> 00:31:04.691
And it's been such
a huge success.

00:31:04.691 --> 00:31:06.440
Because, of course,
people are interested.

00:31:06.440 --> 00:31:07.460
Why wouldn't they be?

00:31:07.460 --> 00:31:09.669
My job is to make them
interested, if I'm interested.

00:31:09.669 --> 00:31:12.168
Then I have to make you-- engage
you-- to get you interested

00:31:12.168 --> 00:31:14.630
in what I'm seeing, and why
I feel it's important for you

00:31:14.630 --> 00:31:15.830
to know this.

00:31:15.830 --> 00:31:21.860
So it has-- it's the kind of
work one does, also, is like--

00:31:21.860 --> 00:31:25.310
and the chance for me
to be part of theater.

00:31:25.310 --> 00:31:28.460
You know, the play on
sexual abuse was, I think,

00:31:28.460 --> 00:31:31.070
particularly moving
because it was

00:31:31.070 --> 00:31:34.220
commissioned by
an NGO that works

00:31:34.220 --> 00:31:36.055
with survivors of sexual abuse.

00:31:36.055 --> 00:31:37.430
And when we did
it, we had people

00:31:37.430 --> 00:31:40.730
after every show
coming and crying

00:31:40.730 --> 00:31:42.800
because their own stories
came back to them,

00:31:42.800 --> 00:31:44.420
which were very suppressed.

00:31:44.420 --> 00:31:46.850
But more than that, men came
to me and said, you know,

00:31:46.850 --> 00:31:50.250
I don't think I'll ever
leave a daughter of mine

00:31:50.250 --> 00:31:53.490
alone with a male
servant ever in my life.

00:31:53.490 --> 00:31:57.130
Even for like half an hour,
because he was so scared.

00:31:57.130 --> 00:32:03.500
And then people said,
why only a young girl?

00:32:03.500 --> 00:32:05.790
Even a young boy
can be molested.

00:32:05.790 --> 00:32:07.950
So I would not leave
any of my children

00:32:07.950 --> 00:32:11.220
alone with somebody I
didn't trust at all.

00:32:11.220 --> 00:32:14.130
So it has a very--

00:32:14.130 --> 00:32:16.020
I don't do only
that kind of work.

00:32:16.020 --> 00:32:19.680
But really, if you use
it as a tool of change,

00:32:19.680 --> 00:32:25.185
it has enormous power, enormous
power, to transform things.

00:32:25.185 --> 00:32:28.890
And the best theater, which I
hope mine does to some extent,

00:32:28.890 --> 00:32:30.890
is that it must make you
look at the world anew.

00:32:30.890 --> 00:32:33.660
To examine things
anew, provoke you

00:32:33.660 --> 00:32:35.880
to think about things
in a different way,

00:32:35.880 --> 00:32:40.350
to re-examine things, to
understand the world anew.

00:32:40.350 --> 00:32:42.390
And the best theatre
does do that.

00:32:42.390 --> 00:32:45.930
The best writing does do that.

00:32:45.930 --> 00:32:47.310
Art can do that.

00:32:47.310 --> 00:32:53.070
So then I started realizing the
power of the performing arts.

00:32:53.070 --> 00:32:56.880
I mean, they're limitless,
as your field is

00:32:56.880 --> 00:33:00.060
limitless in where it can go.

00:33:00.060 --> 00:33:01.770
You know, maybe none
of us will exist.

00:33:01.770 --> 00:33:03.950
They'll just be two
AI sort of types

00:33:03.950 --> 00:33:05.380
sitting over here and talking.

00:33:05.380 --> 00:33:08.460
But whatever, whatever.

00:33:08.460 --> 00:33:09.110
You know?

00:33:09.110 --> 00:33:13.290
So to me, it's that infinite
possibilities of what theatre

00:33:13.290 --> 00:33:17.820
can do, what the stage
can be a crucible for.

00:33:17.820 --> 00:33:20.510
That is very, very exciting.

00:33:20.510 --> 00:33:23.920
AKSHAY THAKKER: So you made a
really good point about theatre

00:33:23.920 --> 00:33:25.990
being a tool to tell stories.

00:33:25.990 --> 00:33:29.330
And you've certainly taken
that across the world.

00:33:29.330 --> 00:33:31.930
And here in the Western world,
we have a very strong theatre

00:33:31.930 --> 00:33:35.170
culture, very strong
theater scene, you know,

00:33:35.170 --> 00:33:37.780
the likes of "The
Book of Mormon."

00:33:37.780 --> 00:33:38.489
Very common name.

