LILLETE DUBEY: Well,
I wouldn't use that

00:33:40.155 --> 00:33:41.520
as my top of the list example.

00:33:41.520 --> 00:33:42.067
[LAUGHING]

00:33:42.067 --> 00:33:44.650
AKSHAY THAKKER: Well, my point
is, these are very common names

00:33:44.650 --> 00:33:45.733
that a lot of people know.

00:33:45.733 --> 00:33:48.794
Now, theatre in India has a
very-- almost a cult following.

00:33:48.794 --> 00:33:50.710
People follow it, and
then most of the country

00:33:50.710 --> 00:33:52.225
doesn't actually follow it.

00:33:52.225 --> 00:33:53.350
Are you seeing this change?

00:33:53.350 --> 00:33:53.850
Are you--

00:33:53.850 --> 00:33:55.679
LILLETE DUBEY: What do you mean?

00:33:55.679 --> 00:33:57.970
AKSHAY THAKKER: Most people,
when you grow up and going

00:33:57.970 --> 00:34:00.830
through India, you don't really
go to theatre or watch plays.

00:34:00.830 --> 00:34:02.462
That's not a thing
most people do.

00:34:02.462 --> 00:34:04.420
LILLETE DUBEY: Because
theatre's never been a--

00:34:04.420 --> 00:34:04.705
AKSHAY THAKKER: Right.

00:34:04.705 --> 00:34:05.500
And this is my question to you.

00:34:05.500 --> 00:34:06.350
LILLETE DUBEY: --habit.

00:34:06.350 --> 00:34:06.590
AKSHAY THAKKER: Right.

00:34:06.590 --> 00:34:07.715
This is my question to you.

00:34:07.715 --> 00:34:09.219
Are you seeing this
change in India?

00:34:09.219 --> 00:34:11.462
Is this culture growing,
or is [INAUDIBLE]??

00:34:11.462 --> 00:34:12.670
LILLETE DUBEY: Yes, yes, yes.

00:34:12.670 --> 00:34:15.610
The thing, I think,
firstly, we have

00:34:15.610 --> 00:34:20.650
a very strong tradition of
what I call the folk theater.

00:34:20.650 --> 00:34:22.389
It's very alive
and very kicking,

00:34:22.389 --> 00:34:24.400
and it's very much there.

00:34:24.400 --> 00:34:27.130
But we're talking about a
more urban kind of theater.

00:34:27.130 --> 00:34:30.040
So that kind of theater
is definitely growing.

00:34:30.040 --> 00:34:33.670
And in some languages-- you
know, India's so diverse.

00:34:33.670 --> 00:34:35.830
I don't know any other
country as diverse as that.

00:34:35.830 --> 00:34:38.679
I mean, 37 languages,
dialects, god

00:34:38.679 --> 00:34:40.239
knows how many
whatever, whatever.

00:34:40.239 --> 00:34:43.960
So I mean, I can't even
count the number of--

00:34:43.960 --> 00:34:46.270
I go down south in
India, and I sometimes

00:34:46.270 --> 00:34:48.520
feel I'm in an alien
country, really,

00:34:48.520 --> 00:34:51.159
sometimes, because
it's so diametrically

00:34:51.159 --> 00:34:53.230
different, the culture.

00:34:53.230 --> 00:34:58.240
And so what I was saying
was that in some states,

00:34:58.240 --> 00:35:02.957
like Gujarat, like
Maharashtra, like let's

00:35:02.957 --> 00:35:05.230
say, Canada, Bangalore.

00:35:05.230 --> 00:35:09.880
In some languages, it's
a thriving culture,

00:35:09.880 --> 00:35:13.930
theater scene, where theater is
done, like Marathi theater, 30

00:35:13.930 --> 00:35:16.770
plays a month, sometimes 35.

00:35:16.770 --> 00:35:19.270
Double ones on
weekends and all that.

00:35:19.270 --> 00:35:22.780
And it's commercially viable,
and people live by theater.

00:35:22.780 --> 00:35:25.550
Gujurati is a very
commercial theater.

00:35:25.550 --> 00:35:30.299
So it's the Hindi and English
theater which is not so--

00:35:30.299 --> 00:35:31.840
you know, but in a
place like Bombay,

00:35:31.840 --> 00:35:33.880
because they have
access, like in New York,

00:35:33.880 --> 00:35:35.302
they can do so
many other things.

00:35:35.302 --> 00:35:36.760
They don't only
have to do theater.

00:35:36.760 --> 00:35:37.860
They can be on television.

00:35:37.860 --> 00:35:38.860
They can do commercials.

00:35:38.860 --> 00:35:40.270
They can host events.

00:35:40.270 --> 00:35:41.300
They can a voicing.

00:35:41.300 --> 00:35:42.610
They can do films.

00:35:42.610 --> 00:35:44.420
They can do web series.

00:35:44.420 --> 00:35:45.730
So they're are working actors.

00:35:45.730 --> 00:35:47.450
They can do lots
of other things.

00:35:47.450 --> 00:35:49.660
But yes, it is not like--

00:35:49.660 --> 00:35:52.260
but let me tell you,
in America also,

00:35:52.260 --> 00:35:55.210
it's only the big Broadway
shows that an actor can actually

00:35:55.210 --> 00:35:56.050
live on.

00:35:56.050 --> 00:36:00.010
If he's doing smaller
theaters, no way.

00:36:00.010 --> 00:36:01.450
He has to do other stuff.

00:36:01.450 --> 00:36:02.220
He has to.

00:36:02.220 --> 00:36:03.810
It's just that in
a Broadway gig,

00:36:03.810 --> 00:36:07.810
he's sure of income for a
year, or so many months,

00:36:07.810 --> 00:36:08.860
or whatever, whatever.

00:36:08.860 --> 00:36:13.470
But then, again, he's out
there auditioning, auditioning,

00:36:13.470 --> 00:36:16.770
auditioning, hoping to
get that next good gig.

00:36:16.770 --> 00:36:19.230
So it's one of the most
uncertain businesses

00:36:19.230 --> 00:36:20.670
in the world, being an actor.

00:36:20.670 --> 00:36:21.690
Let me tell you.

00:36:21.690 --> 00:36:22.530
[LAUGHING]

00:36:22.530 --> 00:36:24.135
AKSHAY THAKKER:
So you were here--

00:36:24.135 --> 00:36:25.300
LILLETE DUBEY: But
things are changing,

00:36:25.300 --> 00:36:26.550
which is what I was coming to.

00:36:26.550 --> 00:36:29.306
A lot of young people are very
interested in doing theater.

00:36:29.306 --> 00:36:31.680
And one of the things we did
do, and I will say it again,

00:36:31.680 --> 00:36:34.620
a little immodestly, is
we were the first to start

00:36:34.620 --> 00:36:36.660
working with Indian writing.

00:36:36.660 --> 00:36:39.514
So once that door opened,
you see we always did,

00:36:39.514 --> 00:36:41.680
especially theatre in,
English, which is derivative.

00:36:41.680 --> 00:36:45.350
We did a Tennessee Williams,
an Arthur Miller, a Neil Simon,

00:36:45.350 --> 00:36:49.320
or of course Shakespeare
and Brecht, from you know,

00:36:49.320 --> 00:36:51.870
whatever, whatever, so
many wonderful playwrights

00:36:51.870 --> 00:36:52.560
in the West.

00:36:52.560 --> 00:36:54.476
And people keep saying,
why don't you do them?

00:36:54.476 --> 00:36:56.750
I said, because the whole
world is there to do them.

00:36:56.750 --> 00:36:58.460
I have to do my stuff.

00:36:58.460 --> 00:37:01.730
Once in a blue moon, I get
seduced by a fabulous script,

00:37:01.730 --> 00:37:02.790
and I do it.

00:37:02.790 --> 00:37:03.951
But that's like, one-off.

00:37:03.951 --> 00:37:04.450
You know.

00:37:04.450 --> 00:37:06.710
Or I feel it's so
universal, like I'm

00:37:06.710 --> 00:37:09.590
doing a play, which
is about the Iraq war,

00:37:09.590 --> 00:37:12.630
about survivors of the Iraq
war between the two Gulf wars.

00:37:12.630 --> 00:37:15.660
And it's just such a
potent piece of theater.

00:37:15.660 --> 00:37:17.990
And it's a one woman show,
which my daughter does.

00:37:17.990 --> 00:37:19.400
And she's incredible in it.

00:37:19.400 --> 00:37:20.780
It's about survival.

00:37:20.780 --> 00:37:21.830
It's about violence.

00:37:21.830 --> 00:37:23.130
It's about the times we live.

00:37:23.130 --> 00:37:24.862
And so it doesn't matter.

00:37:24.862 --> 00:37:25.570
It could be Iraq.

00:37:25.570 --> 00:37:26.510
It could be Timbuktu.

00:37:26.510 --> 00:37:27.954
It could be Bombay.

00:37:27.954 --> 00:37:29.370
We've had terrorist
attacks there.

00:37:29.370 --> 00:37:31.350
We're having them
all over the world.

00:37:31.350 --> 00:37:34.190
So how to survive in
an age of violence.

00:37:34.190 --> 00:37:37.290
And women-- because
you see women

00:37:37.290 --> 00:37:40.010
aren't the ones
who perpetrate it,

00:37:40.010 --> 00:37:42.560
but they are the ones
who live with it.

00:37:42.560 --> 00:37:45.860
Men go out there
to do their stuff,

00:37:45.860 --> 00:37:49.340
to prove themselves, in whatever
way they think they have to.

00:37:49.340 --> 00:37:52.620
But the women pay the price.

00:37:52.620 --> 00:37:55.460
So these are the stories
of women survivors,

00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:57.980
and how they deal with
a 8-year-old child who

00:37:57.980 --> 00:37:59.900
plays with bullets,
makes chains out of them,

00:37:59.900 --> 00:38:03.800
and is very proud of
her little M16 bullets.

00:38:03.800 --> 00:38:06.015
Two women, somebody
in exile who's

00:38:06.015 --> 00:38:09.260
staying in London, who's very
upset about what's going on,

00:38:09.260 --> 00:38:13.670
but can't go then handle it,
to a painter who compromises,

00:38:13.670 --> 00:38:16.460
who does what she has to
do, but she has to paint.

00:38:16.460 --> 00:38:18.170
So she doesn't care.

00:38:18.170 --> 00:38:21.020
So you know, those
stories are so universal,

00:38:21.020 --> 00:38:24.680
that all geographical,
social cultural references

00:38:24.680 --> 00:38:26.510
become absolutely irrelevant.

00:38:26.510 --> 00:38:28.370
Then sometimes I do them.

00:38:28.370 --> 00:38:31.590
But yeah, theater
in Bombay at least,

00:38:31.590 --> 00:38:34.110
it's growing exponentially.

00:38:34.110 --> 00:38:36.980
But we can never compare it to
film, television, and all that.

00:38:36.980 --> 00:38:37.640
You know?

00:38:37.640 --> 00:38:38.865
That's our mistake.

00:38:38.865 --> 00:38:39.740
We keep comparing it.

00:38:39.740 --> 00:38:42.390
It's a niche medium.

00:38:42.390 --> 00:38:44.150
A play of mine, like
"Dance Like a Man,"

00:38:44.150 --> 00:38:46.680
that I've done 600 shows
of, you multiply that even

00:38:46.680 --> 00:38:49.950
by 1,000 people per
show, how many is that?

00:38:49.950 --> 00:38:51.075
Yeah, that's not very many.

00:38:51.075 --> 00:38:52.574
But movies reach
millions of people.

00:38:52.574 --> 00:38:54.030
In one weekend,
somebody will see

00:38:54.030 --> 00:38:57.130
a movie of mine, which is
at least 100 times that.

00:38:57.130 --> 00:38:58.770
So how can you compare the two.

00:38:58.770 --> 00:39:02.520
But look at the freedom you have
artistically, creatively, when

00:39:02.520 --> 00:39:04.710
you do work in the theater.

00:39:04.710 --> 00:39:08.640
You can do that sort of
work in film as an actor,

00:39:08.640 --> 00:39:12.567
or as a director-producer.

00:39:12.567 --> 00:39:14.400
AKSHAY THAKKER: So two
of your cast members,

00:39:14.400 --> 00:39:15.220
Rajeshwari Sachdev and Zila.

00:39:15.220 --> 00:39:16.636
LILLETE DUBEY: Are
very much here.

00:39:16.636 --> 00:39:18.553
Three of them are here
from the play "Gauhar."

00:39:18.553 --> 00:39:20.552
AKSHAY THAKKER: Wonderful,
they're in the crowd.

00:39:20.552 --> 00:39:22.410
Could you tell us a
little bit about how

00:39:22.410 --> 00:39:24.120
you decided to cast
them, and that I'd

00:39:24.120 --> 00:39:25.900
like to bring up on stage
chat with them a little bit.

00:39:25.900 --> 00:39:26.691
LILLETE DUBEY: Yes.

00:39:26.691 --> 00:39:27.560
Very much.

00:39:27.560 --> 00:39:28.800
So I was looking--

00:39:28.800 --> 00:39:31.320
you know, in India,
we don't have

00:39:31.320 --> 00:39:35.070
a concept of training
in musical theater,

00:39:35.070 --> 00:39:36.750
because that needs
special skills.

00:39:36.750 --> 00:39:38.710
You need to be an actor.

00:39:38.710 --> 00:39:40.380
You need to be a good singer.

00:39:40.380 --> 00:39:42.660
You need to be
preferably a good dancer,

00:39:42.660 --> 00:39:44.360
and have enormous
stage presence.

00:39:44.360 --> 00:39:46.790
And that's all, all
rolled into one.

00:39:46.790 --> 00:39:47.890
Nothing much.

00:39:47.890 --> 00:39:50.910
So since we don't have
trained actors like that,

00:39:50.910 --> 00:39:53.940
it's particularly
difficult in India.

00:39:53.940 --> 00:39:56.550
Abroad, they go to
drama school, they

00:39:56.550 --> 00:39:58.750
specialize in musical theater.

00:39:58.750 --> 00:40:00.600
So it's much easier.

00:40:00.600 --> 00:40:03.210
But that didn't dawn
to me, of course.

00:40:03.210 --> 00:40:06.450
And the play was written,
actually, not as a musical.

00:40:06.450 --> 00:40:07.860
I had done musicals.

00:40:07.860 --> 00:40:09.240
This was written
as a play, which

00:40:09.240 --> 00:40:11.140
is a drama about her life.

00:40:11.140 --> 00:40:13.920
And we have to
Gauhar, the younger,

00:40:13.920 --> 00:40:17.380
up to a certain age, and
then the older Gauhar.

00:40:17.380 --> 00:40:22.046
And so, Mahesh, who
adapted it, it's

00:40:22.046 --> 00:40:24.420
from a wonderful book, which
is researched for five years

00:40:24.420 --> 00:40:27.930
by Vikram Sampath on his own
steam at his own expense,

00:40:27.930 --> 00:40:29.467
because he was
fascinated by her.

00:40:29.467 --> 00:40:31.800
I think he was half in love
with this girl [INAUDIBLE]..

00:40:31.800 --> 00:40:33.450
And he wrote the book.

00:40:33.450 --> 00:40:35.400
Then I liked the book very much.

00:40:35.400 --> 00:40:37.740
I asked a very very
eminent playwright of our,

00:40:37.740 --> 00:40:41.970
who was assigned Academy winner,
Mahesh Dattani to write it

00:40:41.970 --> 00:40:43.230
as a play.

00:40:43.230 --> 00:40:45.660
And then there was
this triumvirate talks

00:40:45.660 --> 00:40:47.365
going on, you know,
about, I want this,

00:40:47.365 --> 00:40:48.990
no, I want that, no,
I don't want that,

00:40:48.990 --> 00:40:50.115
and all that sort of thing.

00:40:50.115 --> 00:40:52.136
So finally, we got
the script together.

00:40:52.136 --> 00:40:53.760
And he said, we'll
just play her music.

00:40:53.760 --> 00:40:57.010
Now this is, again,
thanks to Google.

00:40:57.010 --> 00:40:58.320
So how do we find her music?

00:40:58.320 --> 00:41:00.630
Because she sang in 1902.

00:41:00.630 --> 00:41:05.340
And so we Googled her, we went
to YouTube, and found her.

00:41:05.340 --> 00:41:06.840
And I said, oh, my god.

00:41:06.840 --> 00:41:08.880
Because it was a very
primitive recording.

00:41:08.880 --> 00:41:14.070
[INAUDIBLE] records, the
very first records ever made.

00:41:14.070 --> 00:41:19.290
And she did something, and she
was a fabulously fascinating

00:41:19.290 --> 00:41:20.870
woman on many counts.

00:41:20.870 --> 00:41:22.064
I won't go into that.

00:41:22.064 --> 00:41:24.480
But she took up the gauntlet--
she picked up the gauntlet.

00:41:24.480 --> 00:41:29.470
Because an Indian [INAUDIBLE]
can go on for three hours.

00:41:29.470 --> 00:41:32.070
It's just this one phrase,
which you just keep singing,

00:41:32.070 --> 00:41:33.520
and it's like jazz.

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:36.180
You keep improving,
improving, improving.

00:41:36.180 --> 00:41:38.920
And the more of a
virtuoso you are,

00:41:38.920 --> 00:41:41.250
the more you will improv
to show your skills.

00:41:41.250 --> 00:41:42.990
Because there's just
the seven notes,

00:41:42.990 --> 00:41:45.330
and you're doing all
kinds of things with them.

00:41:45.330 --> 00:41:52.350
So she had to do that in
two and and a half minutes.

00:41:52.350 --> 00:41:54.750
She had to do the prelude,
the central section,

00:41:54.750 --> 00:41:56.310
and the climax.

00:41:56.310 --> 00:41:58.800
And all the purests turned
up their noses and said,

00:41:58.800 --> 00:42:00.017
this is blasphemy.

00:42:00.017 --> 00:42:01.350
You can't do this sort of thing.

00:42:01.350 --> 00:42:03.330
And she said, show me the money.

00:42:03.330 --> 00:42:07.160
So they paid us, in those days,
I don't know what it would be.

00:42:07.160 --> 00:42:10.230
3,000 rupees a
recording in 1902.

00:42:10.230 --> 00:42:11.549
What would that be today?

00:42:11.549 --> 00:42:12.090
I don't know.

00:42:12.090 --> 00:42:13.632
How many thousands of dollars?

00:42:13.632 --> 00:42:14.715
AKSHAY THAKKER: Google it.

00:42:14.715 --> 00:42:15.506
LILLETE DUBEY: Huh?

00:42:15.506 --> 00:42:16.137
Google it.

00:42:16.137 --> 00:42:20.860
[LAUGHING] So anyway, some
obscene amount of money.

00:42:20.860 --> 00:42:22.890
And she said, can be done.

00:42:22.890 --> 00:42:25.380
And even her mother
said, what are you doing?

00:42:25.380 --> 00:42:27.040
Our gurus will be very shocked.

00:42:27.040 --> 00:42:28.451
You can't do this sort of thing.

00:42:28.451 --> 00:42:29.700
So she said, I have to try it.

00:42:29.700 --> 00:42:31.030
I'm going to try it.

00:42:31.030 --> 00:42:33.090
And so that's why
she was the first.

00:42:33.090 --> 00:42:34.770
Everybody followed suit later.

00:42:34.770 --> 00:42:36.730
But she said, I will do it.

00:42:36.730 --> 00:42:39.240
So she was a path breaker.

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:42.400
I think it's an appropriate
thing that I found her

00:42:42.400 --> 00:42:45.420
on the net through Google,
and I'm sitting here

00:42:45.420 --> 00:42:48.680
talking about her,
and she, like Google,

00:42:48.680 --> 00:42:53.560
was someone who loved new ideas.

00:42:53.560 --> 00:42:54.180
You know?

00:42:54.180 --> 00:42:56.950
She kept telling her mother,
they had all these patrons,

00:42:56.950 --> 00:42:58.490
these maharajas,
and all, you know,

00:42:58.490 --> 00:43:00.406
who used to call them
for concerts and things.

00:43:00.406 --> 00:43:02.830
And she said the
patrons of the new world

00:43:02.830 --> 00:43:05.737
at the mouths of the New World
would find us our patrons.

00:43:05.737 --> 00:43:08.070
So we don't have to worry
about these maharajas anymore.

00:43:08.070 --> 00:43:10.710
This is technology.

00:43:10.710 --> 00:43:12.700
This is what's going to live.

00:43:12.700 --> 00:43:14.750
You know?

00:43:14.750 --> 00:43:15.500
And she says that.

00:43:15.500 --> 00:43:18.041
There's a moving moment at the
end of the play when she says,

00:43:18.041 --> 00:43:20.010
you know, I went to hear
a concert, and I said,

00:43:20.010 --> 00:43:20.920
this is my music.

00:43:20.920 --> 00:43:22.680
This guy is singing my song.

00:43:22.680 --> 00:43:24.180
And I told everybody,
and they said,

00:43:24.180 --> 00:43:25.860
ha ha, this crazy old lady.

00:43:25.860 --> 00:43:28.140
This biddy, how can
this be her music?

00:43:28.140 --> 00:43:30.330
And she said, it doesn't matter.

00:43:30.330 --> 00:43:32.760
My name also will be
forgotten, but my music

00:43:32.760 --> 00:43:34.500
will live on that record.

00:43:34.500 --> 00:43:36.030
And it will always be there.

00:43:36.030 --> 00:43:37.440
And that is why
we're here today.

00:43:37.440 --> 00:43:38.910
Because our music lessons.

00:43:38.910 --> 00:43:41.820
And we can access it
through technology.

00:43:41.820 --> 00:43:46.120
So much as I am a great
believer in the human touch,

00:43:46.120 --> 00:43:47.370
and I'm really old-fashioned--

00:43:47.370 --> 00:43:51.210
I still prefer smelling
a book, feeling the page,

00:43:51.210 --> 00:43:52.560
all that with my coffee.

00:43:52.560 --> 00:43:54.780
I'm not a Kindle person.

00:43:54.780 --> 00:43:58.080
But having said
that, technology can

00:43:58.080 --> 00:44:02.800
be used very creatively
in the arts as well.

00:44:02.800 --> 00:44:03.300
You know?

00:44:03.300 --> 00:44:05.850
It should not
become a substitute,

00:44:05.850 --> 00:44:08.080
and it shouldn't become
packaging or gimmicky,

00:44:08.080 --> 00:44:10.050
but it can add a lot.

00:44:10.050 --> 00:44:11.850
We've seen it in
so many industries.

00:44:11.850 --> 00:44:14.340
I mean, the music industry,
and this, and that.

00:44:14.340 --> 00:44:15.540
It brings a lot.

00:44:15.540 --> 00:44:17.370
It brings a lot.

00:44:17.370 --> 00:44:19.860
And it also reflects our times.

00:44:19.860 --> 00:44:20.940
These are our times.

00:44:20.940 --> 00:44:22.340
These are technological times.

00:44:22.340 --> 00:44:23.834
So even our art should--

00:44:23.834 --> 00:44:25.500
you don't, I have a
friend [INAUDIBLE]..

00:44:25.500 --> 00:44:32.130
Her husband is doing paintings
on a smartphone with a stylus.

00:44:32.130 --> 00:44:33.570
And he's doing
these exhibitions,

00:44:33.570 --> 00:44:34.800
and they're selling out.

00:44:34.800 --> 00:44:36.840
They're selling
out his paintings.

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:40.920
They not be expensive, but
it's a new way to paint. .

00:44:40.920 --> 00:44:41.940
And it's still art.

00:44:41.940 --> 00:44:43.210
So, it's wonderful.

00:44:43.210 --> 00:44:44.809
I mean, there's
the installations.

00:44:44.809 --> 00:44:45.600
There's visual art.

00:44:45.600 --> 00:44:49.120
There's so much use of
technology now in the arts.

00:44:49.120 --> 00:44:52.050
But as long as we don't
lose the human connect.

00:44:52.050 --> 00:44:54.400
That's all that's important.

00:44:54.400 --> 00:44:56.610
So I had a bit of a problem
because I said, now,

00:44:56.610 --> 00:44:57.420
what I going to do?

00:44:57.420 --> 00:44:59.434
I need two wonderful--

00:44:59.434 --> 00:45:01.350
I mean, I need a wonderful
cast, because there

00:45:01.350 --> 00:45:03.660
are many other wonderful
actors in the play.

00:45:03.660 --> 00:45:07.310
But we need two wonderful
"Gauhars" who can sing,

00:45:07.310 --> 00:45:08.370
who can act.

00:45:08.370 --> 00:45:11.000
So the younger one was
Rajeshwari Sachdev,

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:12.750
who is very talented
actress, who

00:45:12.750 --> 00:45:15.360
also has cut albums and sung.

00:45:15.360 --> 00:45:17.830
And she's a very nice
[NON-ENGLISH] dancer,

00:45:17.830 --> 00:45:20.220
though she's doing
[NON-ENGLISH] in the play.

00:45:20.220 --> 00:45:22.860
And she's a very fine actress.

00:45:22.860 --> 00:45:24.510
National award- winning actress.

00:45:24.510 --> 00:45:27.850
So I sort of zoned into her, and
I said, she's the one I want,

00:45:27.850 --> 00:45:30.210
and she was also very
thrilled with the box.

00:45:30.210 --> 00:45:32.820
Now there was the
older "Gauhar."

00:45:32.820 --> 00:45:37.460
And the play wasn't conceived
with music, but I decided no.

00:45:37.460 --> 00:45:40.010
When I heard those
YouTube scratchy recording

00:45:40.010 --> 00:45:41.696
and this nasal voice,
I said, my God,

00:45:41.696 --> 00:45:43.830
we're doing her a disservice
if we played this.

00:45:43.830 --> 00:45:45.420
People will say,
well, why are they

00:45:45.420 --> 00:45:48.180
doing a play about a woman
who sounded God-awful.

00:45:48.180 --> 00:45:49.757
So we're not going to do that.

00:45:49.757 --> 00:45:51.340
If we're going to
present, we're going

00:45:51.340 --> 00:45:54.390
to present her the
best that she could be,

00:45:54.390 --> 00:45:56.340
as she must have
sounded when she

00:45:56.340 --> 00:45:59.220
sang like this at
the [INAUDIBLE]

00:45:59.220 --> 00:46:00.690
concert or something.

00:46:00.690 --> 00:46:02.972
So that made my job
even more difficult,

00:46:02.972 --> 00:46:04.680
and then I decided I
want live musicians.

00:46:04.680 --> 00:46:07.530
And one of the instruments of
that period was [NON-ENGLISH],,

00:46:07.530 --> 00:46:09.150
which is kind of--
what would you say?

00:46:09.150 --> 00:46:11.070
Kind of violin at that time.

00:46:11.070 --> 00:46:14.420
So there's very few people who
are playing that instrument

00:46:14.420 --> 00:46:17.970
anymore, and a [INAUDIBLE]
player, and a harmonium player,

00:46:17.970 --> 00:46:19.470
and all that.

00:46:19.470 --> 00:46:23.189
And musicians are their
own sort of divas.

00:46:23.189 --> 00:46:24.980
So they say, yeah,
today, [INAUDIBLE] come.

00:46:24.980 --> 00:46:25.480
OK.

00:46:25.480 --> 00:46:28.660
Tomorrow, maybe we can come,
and all that sort of thing.

00:46:28.660 --> 00:46:34.470
So I pulled out a wild
card for the second one.

00:46:34.470 --> 00:46:38.280
I had heard her sing, and
she has a magnificent voice.

00:46:38.280 --> 00:46:40.160
Really magnificent.

00:46:40.160 --> 00:46:43.230
She's a great
[INAUDIBLE] daughter,

00:46:43.230 --> 00:46:45.810
who learned music at
her father's knee,

00:46:45.810 --> 00:46:48.210
where she went at eight
and said she was very

00:46:48.210 --> 00:46:49.920
depressed and extremely sad.

00:46:49.920 --> 00:46:52.560
And he said, why is
that, my darling?

00:46:52.560 --> 00:46:56.460
And she said, because
nobody's teaching me music

00:46:56.460 --> 00:46:58.320
because she was a
girl, and all the boys

00:46:58.320 --> 00:46:59.490
were being taught music.

00:46:59.490 --> 00:47:00.990
So he said, all right.

00:47:00.990 --> 00:47:01.890
We can fix that.

00:47:01.890 --> 00:47:03.910
So she started
learning from him.

00:47:03.910 --> 00:47:06.620
And she's a Sufi
singer, and she sings

00:47:06.620 --> 00:47:08.462
in many, many sort of styles.

00:47:08.462 --> 00:47:10.920
So I'd heard her sing, and I
thought, what a fabulous voice

00:47:10.920 --> 00:47:11.310
she has.

00:47:11.310 --> 00:47:12.570
And I know she hadn't acted.

00:47:12.570 --> 00:47:16.860
I mean, she did something very
small long, long back on stage,

00:47:16.860 --> 00:47:21.440
but she has enormous stage
presence, lovely voice,

00:47:21.440 --> 00:47:23.150
and lovely speaking
voice as well.

00:47:23.150 --> 00:47:24.556
And I said, you know what?

00:47:24.556 --> 00:47:25.680
What I'm going to take her.

00:47:25.680 --> 00:47:28.220
And everyone, oh, she
has a fabulous voice,

00:47:28.220 --> 00:47:30.390
but are you sure you want
to take her as an actor?

00:47:30.390 --> 00:47:32.860
I said, I want to
take her as an actor.

00:47:32.860 --> 00:47:34.280
And she's done a marvelous job.

00:47:34.280 --> 00:47:36.690
I mean, she sings, and
it blows your socks off.

00:47:36.690 --> 00:47:40.560
But that aside, she's done a
lovely job of the play as well.

00:47:40.560 --> 00:47:42.260
So we have these two Gauhars.

00:47:42.260 --> 00:47:46.460
And then, we have Danny Sura,
who plays multiple parts.

00:47:46.460 --> 00:47:48.740
He's an actor who
moved from London.

00:47:48.740 --> 00:47:51.570
He's a trained actor from
London who moved to India.

00:47:51.570 --> 00:47:55.340
And he plays many,
many roles in the play.

00:47:55.340 --> 00:47:57.680
And we have four other actors.

00:47:57.680 --> 00:48:00.260
We have two young actresses
who are from here,

00:48:00.260 --> 00:48:02.610
from the Bay Area,
who have small roles,

00:48:02.610 --> 00:48:06.820
which we case here,
[? Sukanya ?] and [? Sandra, ?]

00:48:06.820 --> 00:48:09.837
the two beauties
sitting next to Danny.

00:48:09.837 --> 00:48:11.420
And then we have
another person called

00:48:11.420 --> 00:48:18.230
Rajiv, who's coming in
tomorrow, and Denzil Smith, who

00:48:18.230 --> 00:48:21.280
plays the father of Gauhar
when she was young and also

00:48:21.280 --> 00:48:26.370
[? Gainsbourg, ?] the American
Anglo-phile sort of engineer

00:48:26.370 --> 00:48:29.060
who went-- he was American,
but he stayed in England,

00:48:29.060 --> 00:48:31.400
so he was more Brit
than an American.

00:48:31.400 --> 00:48:35.540
And he went to look
for the big star

00:48:35.540 --> 00:48:37.280
for the gramophone
company, who would

00:48:37.280 --> 00:48:39.956
sing for the first time
on the vinyl record.

00:48:39.956 --> 00:48:41.330
So there was a
great opera singer

00:48:41.330 --> 00:48:43.520
who sang at the same
time that Gauhar sang.

00:48:43.520 --> 00:48:46.610
So they both sang in
different parts of the world

00:48:46.610 --> 00:48:48.890
and cut a record
at the same time.

00:48:48.890 --> 00:48:50.690
And he comes down.

00:48:50.690 --> 00:48:52.190
I was hoping he'd
be here because he

00:48:52.190 --> 00:48:55.100
has a little lovely speech when
he tells us about how he landed

00:48:55.100 --> 00:48:59.540
here, and how that
one record changed

00:48:59.540 --> 00:49:02.030
the history of
Indian music forever,

00:49:02.030 --> 00:49:04.880
that record that she sang, the
first record that she sang.

00:49:04.880 --> 00:49:06.992
So it's sort of
connected to technology.

00:49:06.992 --> 00:49:08.450
I was thinking
about it last night,

00:49:08.450 --> 00:49:10.160
and I said, how
appropriate that I'm

00:49:10.160 --> 00:49:14.370
coming to Google with Gauhar
and talking about Gauhar,

00:49:14.370 --> 00:49:16.910
which, actually, at
its base, the play

00:49:16.910 --> 00:49:20.850
has the historical
importance of technology.

00:49:20.850 --> 00:49:21.830
Really.

00:49:21.830 --> 00:49:25.220
So that was quite
serendipitous, I think.

00:49:25.220 --> 00:49:26.480
[LAUGHING]

00:49:26.480 --> 00:49:28.795
AKSHAY THAKKER: Let's
invite them on stage.

00:49:28.795 --> 00:49:30.795
LILLETE DUBEY: Rajeshwari
Sachdev and Zila Khan.

00:49:30.795 --> 00:49:33.270
[APPLAUSE]

00:49:38.230 --> 00:49:39.396
LILLETE DUBEY: Come on them.

00:49:39.396 --> 00:49:40.764
Hi, everyone.

00:49:40.764 --> 00:49:41.680
AKSHAY THAKKER: Hello.

00:49:47.410 --> 00:49:54.760
So Rajeshwari, you play the
younger Gauhar in the play.

00:49:54.760 --> 00:49:58.640
How do you balance sort of
adding your own creative touch

00:49:58.640 --> 00:50:02.057
to his character, while still
being true to the real person?

00:50:02.057 --> 00:50:04.140
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV: Oh,
what a difficult question.

00:50:07.590 --> 00:50:11.580
As an actor, it is our job
to understand the part,

00:50:11.580 --> 00:50:14.340
and that only comes with a lot
of study about the character

00:50:14.340 --> 00:50:16.250
that you're doing and
she, unfortunately,

00:50:16.250 --> 00:50:17.589
is not in front of us.

00:50:17.589 --> 00:50:18.630
I'm sorry about my voice.

00:50:18.630 --> 00:50:21.039
A bad case of laryngitis.

00:50:21.039 --> 00:50:23.330
LILLETE DUBEY: But it will
fine by Saturday and Sunday.

00:50:23.330 --> 00:50:25.406
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV: It will
be fine by Saturday, Sunday.

00:50:25.406 --> 00:50:25.906
Yes.

00:50:28.830 --> 00:50:30.000
You have to study your part.

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:32.249
It's very good if you have
a living character to play,

00:50:32.249 --> 00:50:33.420
so you can see the person.

00:50:33.420 --> 00:50:37.650
But we were very fortunate that
Vikram Sampah wrote a book,

00:50:37.650 --> 00:50:39.180
"My Name Is Gauhar Jaan."

00:50:39.180 --> 00:50:40.230
LILLETE DUBEY:
Meticulously researched.

00:50:40.230 --> 00:50:41.850
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV:
Meticulously researched.

00:50:41.850 --> 00:50:42.810
Every little part.

00:50:42.810 --> 00:50:45.540
He tried to piece
together all her letters,

00:50:45.540 --> 00:50:47.160
and what her life
would have been,

00:50:47.160 --> 00:50:48.570
and the society of those times.

00:50:48.570 --> 00:50:52.310
It's so well-explained,
so detailed,

00:50:52.310 --> 00:50:55.920
that it was a cakewalk
after that honestly,

00:50:55.920 --> 00:50:57.961
because it is all
on a platter for us.

00:50:57.961 --> 00:51:00.210
LILLETE DUBEY: But also, I
think it's interesting when

00:51:00.210 --> 00:51:04.200
[INAUDIBLE] is not there,
it also gives you that space

00:51:04.200 --> 00:51:05.490
to fill those that--

00:51:05.490 --> 00:51:07.531
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV: That
also works in the script

00:51:07.531 --> 00:51:09.870
because, obviously, you
can't put the whole book

00:51:09.870 --> 00:51:11.700
in a two-hour play.

00:51:11.700 --> 00:51:14.590
Now, to get that message
across to the audience-- now,

00:51:14.590 --> 00:51:17.130
I have the read book, so I
know where it comes from, what

00:51:17.130 --> 00:51:18.720
we have derived, from where.

00:51:18.720 --> 00:51:21.510
But when as an actor,
I'm piecing together

00:51:21.510 --> 00:51:24.240
bits of our life,
there's a lot that I'm

00:51:24.240 --> 00:51:26.940
bringing to that one scene,
which the audience is not

00:51:26.940 --> 00:51:29.520
fully aware of, because
there's a study that's gone.

00:51:29.520 --> 00:51:33.420
So that's interesting, trying
to put things in between lines,

00:51:33.420 --> 00:51:34.920
in those moments,
and those pauses,

00:51:34.920 --> 00:51:36.750
trying to add that extra.

00:51:36.750 --> 00:51:38.820
That's always an exciting
journey for an actor.

00:51:38.820 --> 00:51:44.490
And I think that's process we
have in every part that we do.

00:51:44.490 --> 00:51:47.070
AKSHAY THAKKER: A lot of us
here in the crowd grew up

00:51:47.070 --> 00:51:50.490
in the indie pop era, and
listening to your work

00:51:50.490 --> 00:51:53.700
was just natural for us.

00:51:53.700 --> 00:51:58.400
So I know you're recovering
from a throat issue.

00:51:58.400 --> 00:52:00.180
So if you're
comfortable with this,

00:52:00.180 --> 00:52:03.010
and if you don't mind singing
us one line of [INAUDIBLE],,

00:52:03.010 --> 00:52:03.860
it would be lovely.

00:52:06.435 --> 00:52:07.560
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV: My god.

00:52:07.560 --> 00:52:08.430
Should I try that?

