But I can try.

00:52:19.170 --> 00:52:20.440
Maybe I cannot really belt it.

00:52:20.440 --> 00:52:23.850
LILLETE DUBEY: Just
a couple of lines.

00:52:23.850 --> 00:52:26.270
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV:
[NON-ENGLISH SINGING]

00:52:47.433 --> 00:52:48.715
LILLETE DUBEY: Lovely.

00:52:48.715 --> 00:52:49.798
AKSHAY THAKKER: Thank you.

00:52:49.798 --> 00:52:51.048
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV: Thank you.

00:52:54.287 --> 00:52:56.370
LILLETE DUBEY: I'm going
to make them sing anyway.

00:52:56.370 --> 00:52:58.890
She's going to sing less,
because she's done her bit.

00:52:58.890 --> 00:53:02.790
AKSHAY THAKKER:
[INAUDIBLE],, you've

00:53:02.790 --> 00:53:06.630
obviously been singing for
a long time in your life.

00:53:06.630 --> 00:53:09.570
How did you prepare for
this role portraying

00:53:09.570 --> 00:53:10.650
a character who has--

00:53:10.650 --> 00:53:13.530
ZILA KHAN: Lillete helped me.

00:53:13.530 --> 00:53:16.300
Every step of the
way, she helped me,

00:53:16.300 --> 00:53:21.990
and she helped me open those
sometimes painful, sometimes

00:53:21.990 --> 00:53:27.270
lovely visuals in your life that
that women and men go through.

00:53:27.270 --> 00:53:28.630
And then she opened--

00:53:28.630 --> 00:53:29.880
and she made it so easy.

00:53:29.880 --> 00:53:32.780
She is a fantastic
director, because--

00:53:32.780 --> 00:53:35.880
and I'm not just saying
it here, because it

00:53:35.880 --> 00:53:37.380
was very difficult for me.

00:53:37.380 --> 00:53:39.690
Singing my concerts,
which I always do,

00:53:39.690 --> 00:53:44.010
is a different skill set, as
Lillete had already mentioned.

00:53:44.010 --> 00:53:46.590
And the play has its own pace.

00:53:46.590 --> 00:53:50.250
When we are doing concerts, we
are doing it at our own pace.

00:53:50.250 --> 00:53:51.700
It is my pace.

00:53:51.700 --> 00:53:53.980
But a play has its
pace of its own,

00:53:53.980 --> 00:53:58.292
and you have to play along
with the pace of the play.

00:53:58.292 --> 00:54:00.000
LILLETE DUBEY: And
you're part of a team.

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:01.780
ZILA KHAN: And the
part of the team,

00:54:01.780 --> 00:54:06.030
the pace of the play, the
back and forth of dialogues.

00:54:06.030 --> 00:54:10.050
And [? now, ?] everybody
helped, including the boys.

00:54:10.050 --> 00:54:14.220
And Lillete's way of
explaining direction really

00:54:14.220 --> 00:54:20.450
helped me a lot, but I've been
fortunate to have lovely gurus.

00:54:20.450 --> 00:54:22.880
My father was an
amazing guru in music.

00:54:22.880 --> 00:54:26.600
He used to explain each
and every little thing

00:54:26.600 --> 00:54:27.830
and open it out.

00:54:27.830 --> 00:54:30.380
And in my acting, this one.

00:54:30.380 --> 00:54:34.870
And this, one this gorgeous
one, who I've enjoyed her talk.

00:54:34.870 --> 00:54:37.580
And I'm so proud of you.

00:54:37.580 --> 00:54:42.840
As an Indian, as a
woman, it's so important

00:54:42.840 --> 00:54:48.570
to be associated with a
production as fabulous as this,

00:54:48.570 --> 00:54:52.530
and in coming here, and
production as fabulous as--

00:54:55.265 --> 00:54:58.305
LILLETE DUBEY:
[INAUDIBLE] She was like--

00:54:58.305 --> 00:55:02.666
[LAUGHING] [INAUDIBLE]
OK, no problem.

00:55:02.666 --> 00:55:05.160
The music was not,
but I must tell you

00:55:05.160 --> 00:55:07.030
that she worked very hard.

00:55:07.030 --> 00:55:10.560
You know, what I loved about
her was that, at this age,

00:55:10.560 --> 00:55:15.780
where you are so, so respected
and admired in your field,

00:55:15.780 --> 00:55:17.910
and you've reached
such a height,

00:55:17.910 --> 00:55:22.290
to challenge yourself and
risk all that in a new area,

00:55:22.290 --> 00:55:24.390
it needs a lot of
courage, and I love that.

00:55:24.390 --> 00:55:26.100
I mean, I love doing new things.

00:55:26.100 --> 00:55:28.740
I love doing new things
to keep myself fresh.

00:55:28.740 --> 00:55:30.720
People say, what's the
best thing you've done?

00:55:30.720 --> 00:55:32.237
What's the best
play you've done?

00:55:32.237 --> 00:55:33.320
The best film you've done?

00:55:33.320 --> 00:55:35.280
Firstly, the best
thing I've ever done

00:55:35.280 --> 00:55:37.350
is produce two children
called Neha and Ira.

00:55:37.350 --> 00:55:38.040
Those are my best productions.

00:55:38.040 --> 00:55:38.967
ZILA KHAN: I agree.

00:55:38.967 --> 00:55:41.610
LILLETE DUBEY: Two best
productions of my life.

00:55:41.610 --> 00:55:44.040
Nothing can compare to that.

00:55:44.040 --> 00:55:47.810
But after them, there
is nothing the best.

00:55:47.810 --> 00:55:50.790
The minute as a creative person
you say, I have done that

00:55:50.790 --> 00:55:54.450
and that was my best, go hang
up your sandals and go home.

00:55:54.450 --> 00:55:55.730
It's all over.

00:55:55.730 --> 00:55:58.286
You are constantly-- the
journey's excitement.

00:55:58.286 --> 00:56:00.910
You know, once I've done a play,
I'm thinking of the next play.

00:56:00.910 --> 00:56:02.340
I'm thinking of the next
thing I'm going to do.

00:56:02.340 --> 00:56:03.590
I mean, I love what I've done.

00:56:03.590 --> 00:56:06.360
It's not like I
disassociate myself with it.

00:56:06.360 --> 00:56:09.246
But my mind's ticking on
what I'm going to do next.

00:56:09.246 --> 00:56:11.400
That next high that
I'm looking for

00:56:11.400 --> 00:56:13.830
is when I create the next piece.

00:56:13.830 --> 00:56:16.500
Then I struggle and find
it, and get it right,

00:56:16.500 --> 00:56:17.910
and then it's never right.

00:56:17.910 --> 00:56:20.340
Let me tell you, nothing I've
ever done is, I feel right.

00:56:20.340 --> 00:56:23.035
I feel there's so much
that could improved in it.

00:56:23.035 --> 00:56:23.854
No role.

00:56:23.854 --> 00:56:25.270
People say, what's
your best role?

00:56:25.270 --> 00:56:29.010
I say maybe if I had done work
like Sarah Bernhardt, maybe I

00:56:29.010 --> 00:56:29.600
[INAUDIBLE].

00:56:29.600 --> 00:56:30.766
I would have done something.

00:56:30.766 --> 00:56:33.700
I want to do all the male
Shakespeare parts myself

00:56:33.700 --> 00:56:38.890
one day, just to
reverse the whole thing.

00:56:38.890 --> 00:56:39.390
But--

00:56:39.390 --> 00:56:42.860
ZILA KHAN: James Bond, when
Angelina Jolie said, yes, I'd

00:56:42.860 --> 00:56:44.630
love to play James Bond myself.

00:56:44.630 --> 00:56:46.356
LILLETE DUBEY: Yeah, yeah.

00:56:46.356 --> 00:56:47.480
And Sarah Bernard did that.

00:56:47.480 --> 00:56:50.940
She was this wonderful
female actress

00:56:50.940 --> 00:56:53.640
who played only the male
parts, Hamlet, and Macbeth.

00:56:53.640 --> 00:56:54.990
And says, move over.

00:56:54.990 --> 00:56:56.670
I'll show you how to do that.

00:56:56.670 --> 00:57:04.440
So-- so, you know, to challenge
yourself anew like that,

00:57:04.440 --> 00:57:06.810
and then you are like
a child, because you're

00:57:06.810 --> 00:57:08.250
coming into an area.

00:57:08.250 --> 00:57:11.200
It's like me trying to
become a computer scientist.

00:57:11.200 --> 00:57:12.600
I mean, I know nothing.

00:57:12.600 --> 00:57:15.270
I become Robert De
Niro, as the intern.

00:57:15.270 --> 00:57:19.630
But all those guys in the Google
movie, you know, my friend--

00:57:19.630 --> 00:57:21.360
what's his name?

00:57:21.360 --> 00:57:22.055
I loved it.

00:57:22.055 --> 00:57:22.680
Those two guys.

00:57:22.680 --> 00:57:24.850
This ripe old age
coming to like, coming

00:57:24.850 --> 00:57:27.360
hang out with the Googlers, and
do their thing and all that.

00:57:27.360 --> 00:57:28.670
And not scared.

00:57:28.670 --> 00:57:29.610
Not scared.

00:57:29.610 --> 00:57:31.410
So that's what she was.

00:57:31.410 --> 00:57:34.890
She was a little Googler who
came to a new space completely.

00:57:34.890 --> 00:57:37.050
And everybody, obviously,
was more trained

00:57:37.050 --> 00:57:38.640
in a sense than her.

00:57:38.640 --> 00:57:40.020
But she was not afraid.

00:57:40.020 --> 00:57:44.566
She was not afraid to sound like
she didn't know, or anything.

00:57:44.566 --> 00:57:45.690
That's a wonderful quality.

00:57:45.690 --> 00:57:47.730
I think that's how you grow.

00:57:47.730 --> 00:57:52.720
You grow when you keep on
exploring latent things in you.

00:57:52.720 --> 00:57:56.170
You know, [INAUDIBLE] leaves
the tech world says, OK,

00:57:56.170 --> 00:57:57.250
enough of that.

00:57:57.250 --> 00:58:00.079
Let's get on let's get into
something called theater.

00:58:00.079 --> 00:58:01.620
Which you might have
done in college,

00:58:01.620 --> 00:58:04.980
but this is another animal,
if you know what I mean.

00:58:04.980 --> 00:58:06.450
So to keep trying new stuff.

00:58:06.450 --> 00:58:09.660
People say, [NON-ENGLISH].

00:58:09.660 --> 00:58:10.180
Regrets.

00:58:10.180 --> 00:58:14.040
Not regrets, but [NON-ENGLISH].

00:58:14.040 --> 00:58:15.660
I said, my gone.

00:58:15.660 --> 00:58:17.670
Every year that I
get older, the clock

00:58:17.670 --> 00:58:19.570
is ticking louder and
louder and louder.

00:58:19.570 --> 00:58:21.570
And I'm saying, heck,
I've got such little time,

00:58:21.570 --> 00:58:22.650
I want to write a book.

00:58:22.650 --> 00:58:24.450
Maybe cut an album one day.

00:58:24.450 --> 00:58:26.820
You know, make some movies.

00:58:26.820 --> 00:58:27.780
Do this, do that.

00:58:27.780 --> 00:58:29.290
I mean, maybe I'll
do none of it.

00:58:29.290 --> 00:58:31.890
But at least the bucket
list is growing that long.

00:58:31.890 --> 00:58:35.205
So I think that's what
keeps you, creatively,

00:58:35.205 --> 00:58:40.050
the juices flowing, is when
you are not scared to keep

00:58:40.050 --> 00:58:42.970
trying things, new things.

00:58:42.970 --> 00:58:46.260
And that's one thing about Zila,
is she worked very, very hard,

00:58:46.260 --> 00:58:47.419
and she was fearless.

00:58:47.419 --> 00:58:49.710
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV: But I
think as a producer/director,

00:58:49.710 --> 00:58:51.559
she was the mos
fearless of the lot.

00:58:51.559 --> 00:58:54.100
Because when she called me and
she said, you're doing Gauhar.

00:58:54.100 --> 00:58:55.250
I said, wow.

00:58:55.250 --> 00:58:55.750
As an actor?

00:58:55.750 --> 00:58:57.010
[INAUDIBLE]

00:58:57.010 --> 00:58:58.510
She says, do you
sing, I said, yeah,

00:58:58.510 --> 00:59:01.050
but I'm not a classical singer.

00:59:01.050 --> 00:59:02.810
I was so scared.

00:59:02.810 --> 00:59:05.200
And those days, I was
filming for something else.

00:59:05.200 --> 00:59:06.210
Every day, I was
to go to the shoot,

00:59:06.210 --> 00:59:07.590
and I would be
singing on the way.

00:59:07.590 --> 00:59:09.840
[INAUDIBLE] But I don't even
know how to [INAUDIBLE]..

00:59:09.840 --> 00:59:13.590
And in the moving cars, I would
OK, [INAUDIBLE],, or something.

00:59:13.590 --> 00:59:15.090
So I told her, I
said, I don't know.

00:59:15.090 --> 00:59:15.870
Yeah.

00:59:15.870 --> 00:59:18.714
So I said, I don't know how good
I will be in the first show.

00:59:18.714 --> 00:59:20.130
LILLETE DUBEY: You
were very good.

00:59:20.130 --> 00:59:21.350
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV:
I don't know how well

00:59:21.350 --> 00:59:22.740
I'm going to pull this off.

00:59:22.740 --> 00:59:24.450
But I promise you,
by the 30th show,

00:59:24.450 --> 00:59:26.040
I'll be standing
there and saying yes,

00:59:26.040 --> 00:59:27.160
yes I can do this well.

00:59:27.160 --> 00:59:28.260
And maybe I'll get better.

00:59:28.260 --> 00:59:29.343
LILLETE DUBEY: [INAUDIBLE]

00:59:29.343 --> 00:59:30.910
[LAUGHING]

00:59:30.910 --> 00:59:36.202
So I wanted them to do a
small song in which, actually,

00:59:36.202 --> 00:59:38.035
they're in costume, and
it's very different,

00:59:38.035 --> 00:59:40.060
and it looks stunning.

00:59:40.060 --> 00:59:41.590
[INAUDIBLE]

00:59:41.590 --> 00:59:45.220
But to do just the
last, one last song,

00:59:45.220 --> 00:59:48.160
when it's a beautiful scene
when the two Gauhars, the older

00:59:48.160 --> 00:59:51.610
Gauhar dies-- and the play keeps
going back and forth in time.

00:59:51.610 --> 00:59:53.560
You know, I mean, not
even chronologically.

00:59:53.560 --> 00:59:59.900
1895 to suddenly
1902, back to 1929,

00:59:59.900 --> 01:00:01.060
back to this, back to that.

01:00:01.060 --> 01:00:03.400
Keeps the audiences nice
and properly on their toes

01:00:03.400 --> 01:00:04.730
to figure out what's going.

01:00:04.730 --> 01:00:08.000
So all of you who are coming
Sunday, I'm warning you.

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:14.300
So at the end when she dies,
it's in a surreal space,

01:00:14.300 --> 01:00:16.300
and the two Gauhars meet,
the young and the old.

01:00:16.300 --> 01:00:20.750
So your own 22-year-old
meets, or whatever,

01:00:20.750 --> 01:00:23.680
30-year-old, meets
your 59-year-old self.

01:00:23.680 --> 01:00:26.020
And we talk a little bit.

01:00:26.020 --> 01:00:30.700
So it's that scene at the end,
which is the penultimate scene.

01:00:30.700 --> 01:00:33.790
And then there's a little song,
which is one of her most--

01:00:33.790 --> 01:00:36.730
when I fell in love with
Gauhar, after I had decided

01:00:36.730 --> 01:00:40.150
to [NON-ENGLISH]
singing this song,

01:00:40.150 --> 01:00:41.740
which she's going
to sing just now.

01:00:41.740 --> 01:00:43.540
And it made my hair rise.

01:00:43.540 --> 01:00:46.600
And I said, my god, her
song is still being sung.

01:00:46.600 --> 01:00:48.389
And [INAUDIBLE],, of
course, rocked it.

01:00:48.389 --> 01:00:50.430
And she was very impressed,
because I went to her

01:00:50.430 --> 01:00:52.312
and I said, isn't this
Gauhar Jaan's song?

01:00:52.312 --> 01:00:53.770
And she looked at
me, and she said,

01:00:53.770 --> 01:00:56.930
my god, I didn't know you know
so much about classical music.

01:00:56.930 --> 01:00:58.639
And I said, well, one
knows a little bit.

01:00:58.639 --> 01:01:00.221
And then I said I
better bullshit her.

01:01:00.221 --> 01:01:00.850
I said, no, no.

01:01:00.850 --> 01:01:03.492
Actually, I'm just
doing this play.

01:01:03.492 --> 01:01:05.900
[LAUGHING]

01:01:05.900 --> 01:01:07.360
I though there was
something here.

01:01:07.360 --> 01:01:10.540
You seem too well-acquainted
with all her music.

01:01:10.540 --> 01:01:12.287
So I say, yeah, well.

01:01:12.287 --> 01:01:13.120
I'm doing her music.

01:01:13.120 --> 01:01:14.230
That's how I know it.

01:01:14.230 --> 01:01:15.610
So it's a stunning song.

01:01:15.610 --> 01:01:17.584
And I would love her to sing it.

01:01:17.584 --> 01:01:19.500
I'm not going to-- they
both sing it together.

01:01:19.500 --> 01:01:20.833
But because her voice is not OK.

01:01:20.833 --> 01:01:22.810
But she dances the
[NON-ENGLISH] with it.

01:01:22.810 --> 01:01:25.120
So you get a feel of
the play, and we we're

01:01:25.120 --> 01:01:27.160
going to get off the stage now.

01:01:27.160 --> 01:01:31.180
ZILA KHAN: So I had learned
Gauhar Jaan's [NON-ENGLISH]

01:01:31.180 --> 01:01:34.270
and many thousands of different
kinds of [NON-ENGLISH] from

01:01:34.270 --> 01:01:37.850
different [NON-ENGLISH] from
my father since I was a child.

01:01:37.850 --> 01:01:40.210
So when this [INAUDIBLE]
came to me, so

01:01:40.210 --> 01:01:45.700
it was quite something that
I've already learned from.

01:01:45.700 --> 01:01:49.060
And it's one of the most
beautiful pieces of Gauhar's,

01:01:49.060 --> 01:01:50.920
and I'm so--

01:01:50.920 --> 01:01:52.930
all your pieces that
you have selected

01:01:52.930 --> 01:01:56.350
and the songs in
the how of Gauhar

01:01:56.350 --> 01:01:59.620
is exceptionally beautiful.

01:01:59.620 --> 01:02:01.930
Shall we start?

01:02:01.930 --> 01:02:03.210
[INAUDIBLE], are we ready?

01:02:05.830 --> 01:02:09.870
So now, there's
just the two of us.

01:02:09.870 --> 01:02:13.754
Who was the person you
were hoping to meet here?

01:02:13.754 --> 01:02:15.520
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV: Ami?

01:02:15.520 --> 01:02:16.480
Where is she?

01:02:16.480 --> 01:02:17.640
Have you seen her?

01:02:17.640 --> 01:02:20.106
ZILA KHAN: She's
right here with us.

01:02:20.106 --> 01:02:25.100
[SIGHING]

01:02:25.100 --> 01:02:28.016
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV:
She always [INAUDIBLE]..

01:02:28.016 --> 01:02:28.940
Here it is.

01:02:32.180 --> 01:02:36.560
You have to keep breaking
your heart until it opens.

01:02:40.880 --> 01:02:46.304
You have to keep breaking
your heart until it opens.

01:02:46.304 --> 01:02:49.210
It's opened.

01:02:49.210 --> 01:02:50.168
ZILA KHAN: It's opened.

01:02:53.206 --> 01:02:55.580
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV: Let's
celebrate the way we know best.

01:02:55.580 --> 01:02:56.780
With a song.

01:02:56.780 --> 01:03:00.100
ZILA KHAN: Not any song,
but the one we love best.

01:03:00.100 --> 01:03:01.900
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV: That one?

01:03:01.900 --> 01:03:03.350
Don't you feel sad singing it?

01:03:03.350 --> 01:03:04.460
ZILA KHAN: Not anymore.

01:03:04.460 --> 01:03:08.410
[LAUGHING]

01:03:08.410 --> 01:03:12.112
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV:
Our sad song.

01:03:12.112 --> 01:03:15.100
Let's make it a happy one.

01:03:15.100 --> 01:03:20.080
[NON-ENGLISH SINGING]

01:06:11.622 --> 01:06:13.229
[APPLAUSE]

01:06:13.229 --> 01:06:14.353
RAJESHWARI SACHDEV: Thanks.

01:06:17.305 --> 01:06:19.430
AKSHAY THAKKER: I want to
bring up one more person.

01:06:19.430 --> 01:06:21.590
We have Vinita Belani.

01:06:21.590 --> 01:06:25.280
She is a part of EnActe Arts.

01:06:25.280 --> 01:06:29.120
She brought this
play and many other--

01:06:29.120 --> 01:06:31.880
she brings many other the
productions here to the US.

01:06:31.880 --> 01:06:36.875
So let's bring Vinita up on
stage and hear more about.

01:06:36.875 --> 01:06:38.234
VINITA BELANI: Thanks.

01:06:38.234 --> 01:06:41.250
AKSHAY THAKKER: Hi,
Vinita Could you tell us

01:06:41.250 --> 01:06:45.330
a little bit about your
company, and what else is coming

01:06:45.330 --> 01:06:47.160
in the pipeline for you here?

01:06:47.160 --> 01:06:49.410
VINITA BELANI: Well,
everybody heard Lillete talk.

01:06:49.410 --> 01:06:51.660
Everybody understands the
compulsion for theater.

01:06:51.660 --> 01:06:54.280
Everybody understands
the importance by now.

01:06:54.280 --> 01:06:56.430
If you haven't
understood it, I don't

01:06:56.430 --> 01:06:59.490
know anybody who could be
more articulate than Lillete

01:06:59.490 --> 01:07:00.660
on the idea.

01:07:00.660 --> 01:07:03.510
And just Lillete started her
theatre company years and years

01:07:03.510 --> 01:07:07.680
ago, because there was a vacuum,
there were Indian stories were

01:07:07.680 --> 01:07:12.537
not being told in English, I
said that I have to confess--

01:07:12.537 --> 01:07:14.120
I'm almost embarrassed
to confess this

01:07:14.120 --> 01:07:16.907
after Lillete's talk, that
I am a computer scientist.

01:07:16.907 --> 01:07:19.392
[LAUGHING]

01:07:20.890 --> 01:07:25.520
So I lived in the tech
world for a long time.

01:07:25.520 --> 01:07:27.070
I did three start-ups.

01:07:27.070 --> 01:07:28.950
EnActe is my fourth startup.

01:07:28.950 --> 01:07:30.890
It's very much a
Silicon Valley startup.

01:07:30.890 --> 01:07:32.310
We are a talent incubator.

01:07:32.310 --> 01:07:34.020
We are bootstrapped
in the garage.

01:07:34.020 --> 01:07:36.645
We went through our friends
and family round of funding

01:07:36.645 --> 01:07:38.950
and now going to a
series A funding,

01:07:38.950 --> 01:07:40.650
which is why Lillete is here.

01:07:40.650 --> 01:07:44.520
She's our centerpiece
for our gala on Saturday.

01:07:44.520 --> 01:07:48.650
So we are using tech,
as Gauhar used tech,

01:07:48.650 --> 01:07:56.640
to change the history of music,
in many ways, in [INAUDIBLE]..

01:07:56.640 --> 01:08:02.780
But we are now in the
diaspora of South Asians,

01:08:02.780 --> 01:08:08.400
people originally from South
Asian, a significant community.

01:08:08.400 --> 01:08:11.010
And we are sitting on
the edge of two cultures,

01:08:11.010 --> 01:08:12.066
the culture that--

01:08:12.066 --> 01:08:13.440
at least our
children are sitting

01:08:13.440 --> 01:08:15.604
on the edge of two
cultures, and we are sort of

01:08:15.604 --> 01:08:17.520
on the edge of two
cultures, which the culture

01:08:17.520 --> 01:08:19.859
that we came from, the
culture that we live in.

01:08:19.859 --> 01:08:22.109
So EnActe does a
lot of work which

01:08:22.109 --> 01:08:25.620
is layered in
diaspora playwrights.

01:08:25.620 --> 01:08:28.890
We are a talent incubator in
all aspects of the theater--

01:08:28.890 --> 01:08:32.790
playwrighting, stage management,
acting, music, dance,

01:08:32.790 --> 01:08:34.250
performance.

01:08:34.250 --> 01:08:37.600
As a female artistic director
of a theater company,

01:08:37.600 --> 01:08:41.700
I feel very compelled to
tell the stories of women

01:08:41.700 --> 01:08:44.370
who can be strong role
models for our daughters

01:08:44.370 --> 01:08:45.366
and for our sons.

01:08:45.366 --> 01:08:47.490
We did a play last year
called "Sound Waves," which

01:08:47.490 --> 01:08:49.350
is the story of [INAUDIBLE].

01:08:49.350 --> 01:08:51.210
She was this young
Muslim girl living

01:08:51.210 --> 01:08:56.410
in Paris, daughter of a Sufi
preacher, who joined the World

01:08:56.410 --> 01:09:01.920
War II spy movement
because she was

01:09:01.920 --> 01:09:05.370
compelled, even as a
pacifist, to do something

01:09:05.370 --> 01:09:06.510
to stop the war.

01:09:06.510 --> 01:09:07.710
And she got a George Cross.

01:09:07.710 --> 01:09:10.920
She was given the
[INAUDIBLE] by France.

01:09:10.920 --> 01:09:14.189
Churchill admitted
that she had--

01:09:14.189 --> 01:09:18.000
she had reduced the course of
World War II by at least four

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:20.729
to six months, just with her
work in the French resistance

01:09:20.729 --> 01:09:22.229
alone.

01:09:22.229 --> 01:09:24.540
And even I hadn't heard
about [INAUDIBLE]..

01:09:24.540 --> 01:09:27.300
So these are stories
that need to be told.

01:09:27.300 --> 01:09:30.090
Vikram Sampath, who wrote the
book "My Name is "Gauhar Jaan,"

01:09:30.090 --> 01:09:33.780
is a classmate of mine from
[INAUDIBLE],, also an engineer.

01:09:33.780 --> 01:09:34.680
[LAUGHING]

01:09:34.680 --> 01:09:38.160
Sometimes we do some
things right, right?

01:09:38.160 --> 01:09:40.350
And somebody had
given me his book.

01:09:40.350 --> 01:09:41.460
And I said, oh, my gosh.

01:09:41.460 --> 01:09:42.850
I wish someone would
write a play about this

01:09:42.850 --> 01:09:43.792
so we could do it.

01:09:43.792 --> 01:09:46.000
And then we found out that
the play had been written,

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:48.584
and Lillete had done it.

01:09:48.584 --> 01:09:49.250
So there you go.

01:09:49.250 --> 01:09:51.380
Between this and
there, and "Gauhar"

01:09:51.380 --> 01:09:53.127
is a story that
needs to be told.

01:09:53.127 --> 01:09:54.960
There are many stories
that need to be told.

01:09:54.960 --> 01:10:00.180
But EnActe exists because
our stories are not

01:10:00.180 --> 01:10:06.930
being told in the
demographic in which we live.

01:10:06.930 --> 01:10:09.380
We are telling them to
our own people-- everybody

01:10:09.380 --> 01:10:12.740
here in the Bay
Area, for example,

01:10:12.740 --> 01:10:14.990
there is no demographic
majority anymore.

01:10:14.990 --> 01:10:16.760
There's a whole
bunch of minorities,

01:10:16.760 --> 01:10:21.030
and all these minorities are
practicing their art in silos.

01:10:21.030 --> 01:10:23.900
And we are trying to
break these cultural silos

01:10:23.900 --> 01:10:28.790
and give our children an
opportunity to grow and develop

01:10:28.790 --> 01:10:30.680
their talent.

01:10:30.680 --> 01:10:32.720
For every 10 people
who become engineers,

01:10:32.720 --> 01:10:34.820
there is that one
11th person that does

01:10:34.820 --> 01:10:37.640
want to become an
[INAUDIBLE],, or a [INAUDIBLE]..

01:10:37.640 --> 01:10:41.030
So where is the training
ground for these people?

01:10:41.030 --> 01:10:42.530
The training ground is EnActe.

01:10:42.530 --> 01:10:49.220
And here's my two
wonderful trainees.

01:10:49.220 --> 01:10:50.330
We're a talent incubator.

01:10:50.330 --> 01:10:52.760
We tell stories from South Asia.

01:10:52.760 --> 01:10:54.270
We have a lot of fun doing it.

01:10:54.270 --> 01:10:55.787
And we do it in all humility.

01:10:55.787 --> 01:10:56.870
AKSHAY THAKKER: Wonderful.

01:10:56.870 --> 01:10:59.931
What's coming next to the Bay
Area that you're bringing?

01:10:59.931 --> 01:11:02.180
VINITA BELANI: Oh, thank you
for asking that question,

01:11:02.180 --> 01:11:06.200
because I'm directing
a play that we

01:11:06.200 --> 01:11:08.120
had commissioned by a
Hollywood script writer

01:11:08.120 --> 01:11:10.280
called "My Fair Dude."

01:11:10.280 --> 01:11:13.700
It's a sort of tongue in
cheek, tongue in cheek,

01:11:13.700 --> 01:11:17.210
take on the original
"My Fair Lady" story,

01:11:17.210 --> 01:11:18.620
the Pygmalion story.

01:11:18.620 --> 01:11:22.340
But it is set right
here in Silicon Valley.

01:11:22.340 --> 01:11:27.920
The protagonist is a
young, nerdy engineer,

01:11:27.920 --> 01:11:29.930
living and working
in a tech company.

01:11:29.930 --> 01:11:33.110
And he's having trouble dating.

01:11:33.110 --> 01:11:34.351
And [LAUGHING].

01:11:34.351 --> 01:11:34.850
See?

01:11:34.850 --> 01:11:37.504
Everybody identifies with this.

01:11:37.504 --> 01:11:39.920
And he's having trouble dating
because he hasn't quite got

01:11:39.920 --> 01:11:42.320
the social dynamic straight.

01:11:42.320 --> 01:11:44.740
And he gets helped
by a girl called

01:11:44.740 --> 01:11:48.650
Abby, who is the VP of
technology at his company.

01:11:48.650 --> 01:11:52.370
She just happens to be
very lesbian, very bad ass.

01:11:52.370 --> 01:11:58.894
And she takes him in hand, and
she finds him a tutor, who is--

01:11:58.894 --> 01:12:00.310
and I won't reveal
the rest of it,

01:12:00.310 --> 01:12:02.143
because you'll just
have to come and see it.

01:12:02.143 --> 01:12:04.667
But that is a story about
people like you, and my kids,

01:12:04.667 --> 01:12:07.000
and everybody who's living
here in Silicon Valley in San

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:08.470
Francisco.

01:12:08.470 --> 01:12:11.620
It's an out and out
slapstick Broadway

01:12:11.620 --> 01:12:15.230
musical, song and dance,
hoohaa kind of play.

01:12:15.230 --> 01:12:17.200
We do some of those too.

01:12:17.200 --> 01:12:19.000
AKSHAY THAKKER: When
is this scheduled to--

01:12:19.000 --> 01:12:20.625
VINITA BELANI: That's
coming up in May.

01:12:20.625 --> 01:12:22.210
AKSHAY THAKKER: Excellent.

01:12:22.210 --> 01:12:24.168
VINITA BELANI: Before
that, we are doing a play

01:12:24.168 --> 01:12:26.710
that we opened in January
in San Francisco called

01:12:26.710 --> 01:12:29.934
"The Party," which is a
very intense and a very

01:12:29.934 --> 01:12:31.600
gut-wrenching kind
of play, because it's

01:12:31.600 --> 01:12:35.230
the story of partition told by
the survivors of partition who

01:12:35.230 --> 01:12:37.214
crossed the line on both sides.

01:12:37.214 --> 01:12:38.630
AKSHAY THAKKER:
Thank you so much.

01:12:38.630 --> 01:12:40.922
Good luck with "Gauhar" and
all your other productions.

01:12:40.922 --> 01:12:42.296
VINITA BELANI:
Yes, and thank you

01:12:42.296 --> 01:12:44.740
for having Lillete and all of
these wonderful people here.

01:12:44.740 --> 01:12:46.160
And thank you for
inviting me as well.

01:12:46.160 --> 01:12:47.243
AKSHAY THAKKER: Of course.

01:12:47.243 --> 01:12:48.110
Thank you.

01:12:48.110 --> 01:12:51.460
[APPLAUSE]

